<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Protests Against Killing of Lawyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Nationalist Party(
BNP)- led four-party opposition alliance Monday staged country-
wide demonstrations protesting against the killing of two lawyers
in the country by gunmen.
</P>
<P>
As part of the demonstration program, the main opposition BNP
and its allies -- Jatiya Party, Jamaat-e- Islam and Islami Oikya
Jote(Islami Solidarity Front) held rallies separately in the
capital before bringing out processions in the city. The
demonstrations and processions ended peacefully Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
A BNP lawyer was shot dead by gunmen in the capital on Sunday
morning and a lawyer of the ruling Awami League was shot dead on
the same day by gunmen in Bagerhat town, 370 kilometers southwest
of Dhaka. the motives behind the killings were not known
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance has called half-day general strike on
August 23 and dawn to dusk general strike on August 30 across the
country in protest against the killings.
</P>
<P>
Addressing rallies in the capital Sunday, opposition leaders
pointed out that killing is a regular affair today and law and
order situation totally collapsed. Jatiya Party Chairman and
former President Hussain Mohammad Ershad said that "fall of this
government is a must today" to save the people and the existence
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance which had earlier decided to launch a
militant movement from mid-September now plans to intensify the
oust-government towards the end of this month following the
killing of the lawyers and the price hike of gas and petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
Opposition sources claimed that there are now a number of "hot
issues", including the price increase of fuel, prime minister's
remarks on the judiciary, deterioration of law and order and
teachers' strike.
</P>
<P>
The government on last Monday suddenly increased the prices of
fuel oil and on last Wednesday made an announcement to enhance the
price of gas by 15 percent from September 1.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that the price hike will have a far reaching
negative impact on the cost of power, fertilizer, industrial and
agricultural products and above all, the cost of living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
