<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliamentarian Visits Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Housei Norota, a senior Japanese
Parliamentarian and former Cabinet Minister who is currently on
his visit to Sri Lanka as a special envoy of Japanese Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori, held talks here with Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A press release by Sri Lankan Foreign Ministry said that
Kumaratunga briefed Norota on recent political and economic
development in Sri Lanka and the steps taken by the Sri Lankan
government to politically resolve the long-running ethnic conflict
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Norota said that Japan was following the development in Sri
Lanka very closely and the Japanese government appreciated the
efforts made by President Kumaratunga to restore peace in the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the talks Kumaratunga expressed her hope that Japanese
Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori would visit Sri Lanka in the near
future. No Japanese Prime Minister has visited Sri Lanka in the
last 10 years, the press release noted.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese special envoy also met with Sri Lankan Foreign
Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar. Both sides exchanged views on
bilateral relations as well as on international and regional
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
