<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's newly-appointed
representative in south Lebanon Rolf Knutsson Monday made his first
tour of the U.N.-drawn Blue Line since he arrived in the country,
As Safir newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish envoy told reporters at Sheikh Abbad hill, one of
the two border points where his convoy stopped for a field
verification, that his mission was to make sure that U.N. Security
Council Resolutions 425 and 426 had been implemented after Israel
withdrew its troops from south Lebanon on May 24. (Lebanon-UN-Blue
Line)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Jordan's King Abdullah II made a short visit to
Israel Tuesday, urging both Israelis and Palestinians not to miss
the chance to end decades of conflict by reaching a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at
the Defense Ministry in the city.
</P>
<P>
Although no official release about the talks was given, an
Israeli source said the two leaders exchanged views on how to move
the Middle East peace process forward, particularly the issues
concerning the Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks. (Israel-
Jordanian King-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Three children were killed and another one injured
Tuesday afternoon in an explosion in south Lebanon, ANN television
station reported.
</P>
<P>
Witness said the kids were playing near a former Israeli
position at the village of Braishit in south Lebanon. "They found a
metal and picked it up to see it, then the mine or a shell
exploded," said a boy who saw the tragedy. (Lebanon-Mine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is scheduled to
address an Arab foreign ministers meeting in Cairo on September 3
about the peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel, Arab
League's spokesman Talaat Hamad said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will focus on the latest developments of the Palestinian-
Israeli peace negotiations and his recent efforts to win support
form world countries for the Palestinian cause, Hamad told Egypt's
Middle East News Agency. (Arab League-Palestine-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Jeremiah Mattysse, the American intelligence
officer reported missing from his Texas base and was later found in
Israel, left the country Tuesday aboard an Israeli flight bound for
New York.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy and the Israeli authorities said the 50-year-
old Christian-turned Judaist decided to return the U.S. willingly,
but Mattysse's attorney Yoram Sheftel held that the officer had
left under strong pressure. (Israel-"Convert Spy"-Return) 
</P>
</TEXT>
