<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Warned Not to Buy Greek Cypriot Property in Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government on Tuesday
warned foreigners against buying the property left over by the
Greek Cypriots who were evicted by the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Anybody buying Greek Cypriot property in northern Cyprus through
illegal means should know they will not be able to keep it, the
Cyprus government warned.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during his first briefing after returning from his
summer holidays, government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said the
government will not condone under any circumstances such purchases.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou made the remarks in response to reports in the
British press that British and German nationals have bought or
leased property belonging to Greek Cypriots from Turkish Cypriots
or Turks in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern the third of the island in the wake of a failed coup
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greek Cypriots who fled the Turkish Cypriot north as the Turkish
troops advanced in the summer of 1974, left behind millions of
dollars worth of property.
</P>
<P>
Titina Loizidou, a Greek Cypriot woman, who owns a property in
northern Cyprus, took her case to the European Court of Human
Rights of the Council of Europe against Turkey and won her right
and access to her property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
