<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biotechnology, Pharmaceutical Firms Form International Data Consortium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A multinational group of
biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies have formed a
consortium aimed at establishing common computing standards for
data and information analyses related to gene-based drug
development.
</P>
<P>
The launch of BioPathways Consortium was announced Tuesday at
an international conference on intelligent systems for molecular
biology held in San Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the consortium was organized by 3rd
Millennium, a U.S. consultancy firm focused on genomics and life
science informatics, in partnership with Hybrigenics, a Paris-
based functional proteomics and bioinformatic company.
</P>
<P>
Genomics-related information has been accumulated by thousands
of companies, government agencies and academic institutions
worldwide, with literally dozens of different formats, said the
new group in a statement. The lack of a single information
standard worldwide prevents intelligent linking and sharing of
information and is considered to be a major obstacle to more rapid
development of gene-based pharmaceutical and other products.
</P>
<P>
"The Consortium is being formed to develop wholly new
information technologies needed to support the accrual,
organization, analyses, and efficient access of genomic
information," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The group will be working to set new standards for data on
biologically important pathways and interactions, the targets of
the industry effort underway to development pharmaceuticals and
other products which act on genetic and molecular bases of
diseases. Specifically, it will target the development of
computing information standards related to biochemical pathways --
all forms of molecular exchanges and processes which can involve
linear processing, cyclic phenomena, branched pathways or complex
combinations of all three.
</P>
<P>
Immediate objectives of the consortium include identification
of specific needs for informatics standards related to genomics
and proteomics research and development of Web-based venues for
discussion and sharing of relevant software tools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Fights Against Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Minister for Agriculture
Alfonso Pecoraro Scanio Tuesday called for the installation of
forest watchtowers as another in a battery of measures designed to
control the fires that have already devastated over 66,000
hectares of countryside this year.
</P>
<P>
Before going on summer vacation, the government approved an
emergency measure introducing the crime of forest arson with a
jail sentence from two to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
In another measure, Pecoraro Scanio, who is responsible for the
country's Forestry Corps with its mix of policing and
environmental tasks, set up a national forest arson investigative
unit on the lines of similar anti-Mafia units.
</P>
<P>
This year, the surface area burned by fire has risen by about
20 percent, and the number of fires has risen from 4,978 to 7,282
with 2,193 in August alone, the Forestry Corps said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But, despite the rise in surface area burned, the corps said
less woodland was destroyed, 26,571 against 31,730 hectares, and
the average surface area per fire fell from 11.4 to 9.1 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Half the fires were in southern Italy which by itself accounted
for 594 fires in the first 20 days of August. But in the last few
days the fire front has also shifted north.
</P>
<P>
The situation was said to be critical in the central region of
Umbria, with most of the blazes traceable to arson.
</P>
<P>
Pecoraro Scanio said he hopes to get several million U.S.
dollars from the next budget to the regional government, which is
now responsible for the environment, to build the watchtowers, "at
least in national and regional parks and areas where each summer
sees a fire emergency." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
