<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Police Seize Record-breaking Ecstasy Tablets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A joint force of Canadian police,
Customs and railway officials have seized 340,000 illegal pills
known as ecstasy with street value of 11 million Canadian dollars
(about 7.5 million U.S. dollars), Canadian police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the biggest seizure of ecstasy in Canadian history. The
previous record-breaking catch of 144,000 pills was reported in
May at Montreal's Dorval International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Two Toronto men are being charged with smuggling the drugs
originated from Belgium after they were found in a railway
shipment bound for Toronto from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Ecstasy, an amphetamine taken to fuel non-stop dancing, can
lead to death through heat exhaustion, dehydration and kidney and
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
Seven ecstasy-related deaths have been reported in Toronto for
the first half of the year, compared with nine in all of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
