<HEADLINE> Iraq Sends Telegram of Condolence to Russia Over Kursk Sub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
Tuesday sent a telegram of condolence to Russian President Vladimir
Putin over the tragic accident of the sunken submarine Kursk, the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In the telegram, the Iraqi president expressed his consolation
to the government and people of Russia, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel so sorry for this disaster," the telegram said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Northern Fleet Commander Vyacheslav Popov, who was in
charge of the rescue operation, has confirmed that all the 118 crew
of the sunken submarine are dead.
</P>
<P>
"After jointly examining the Russian nuclear submarine Kursk
that sank in the Barents Sea during a military exercise on August
12, Russian and foreign experts have made the final conclusion that
the entire submarine is flooded and all the 118 crew are dead," the
Russian Interfax News Agency cited Popov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been a traditional ally and the biggest trade partner
of Iraq. 
</P>
