<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Reforms Must Comply with Constitution: Khatami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
stressed here on Tuesday that reforms in the country should be in
conformity with the constitution and not violate the fundamentals
of Islam.
</P>
<P>
The reforms in the political, cultural and economic fields
should comply with the constitution, and they should not be defined
as means to topple the Islamic republic, Khatami said on the
occasion of the third anniversary of his inauguration as president.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state broadcasting network, he stressed
that people's freedom and fundamental rights should be protected,
but freedom and rights should not violate the law and Islamic
principles.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won a landslide victory in the presidential election in
1997 on account of his advocates for political and social reforms.
</P>
<P>
Since he took office, the political atmosphere in the country
has become more and more active, as seen through the emergence of a
large number of political parties and outspoken newspapers.
</P>
<P>
In February, the sixth parliamentary election was held with a
high rate of public participation and Khatami's reformist allies
won an overwhelming victory over their conservative opponents.
</P>
<P>
The victory showed that Khatami's reform programs had gained
widespread support among the people, who were tired of the long-
time political and social restrictions imposed by the conservative
establishment.
</P>
<P>
However, the reformist victory in February caused concern among
the conservatives, or the guardians of the restrictive cleric rule,
who are still controlling most of the key state organs, including
the judiciary and the military.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, the conservative judiciary has ordered
the closure of more than 20 reformist papers and journals and
imprisoned many reformist activists on the so-called charges of
violating Islamic values and advocating pro-American reforms.
</P>
<P>
Aware of their weakness, Khatami and his reformist allies have
thus far maintained restraint in face of the conservative
retaliation. They claim that they, too, are loyal to the Islamic
system and all reforms should not conflict with Islamic values and
principles.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has announced that he will seek a second term in next
year's presidential election. With both the reformist and
conservative factions launching their campaign, the 2000 race will
certainly be tougher than that in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
