<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abdullah Ends Visit to Israel EDS-2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Abdullah II ended
his short visit to Israel Tuesday afternoon, urging both Israelis
and Palestinians not to miss the chance to end decades of conflict
by reaching a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who flew to Israel's seaport city of Tel Aviv earlier
in the day from the West Bank city of Ramallah, held talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at the Defense Ministry in the
city.
</P>
<P>
Although no official release about the talks was given, an
Israeli source said the two leaders exchanged views on how to move
the Middle East peace process forward, particularly the issues
concerning the Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah did raise the issues such as the Palestinian refugees
and Jerusalem, which broke down the U.S.-sponsored Camp David
summit in July, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the country most intricately linked to the Israeli-
Palestinian peace talks, because it is home to about 1.5 million
Palestinian refugees. Jordan also wants to seek a large
compensation package for hosting these refugees and urges Israel to
allow at least some of the refugees to return.
</P>
<P>
However, the source added, Abdullah neither made any new
specific proposals for their settlement nor suggestions for a
breakthrough of the Israeli-Palestinian track during the talks.
</P>
<P>
He listened carefully to Barak's view on moving the peace
process forward and encouraged Barak to pursue a further round of
talks with Palestinians and Syria, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks, Abdullah told reporters that to further the
negotiations is the only option for solving the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides are in dialog, and that is a healthy thing when
people are communicating, are trying to overcome the obstacles.
Both sides are committed to moving this process forward and our job
and that of the rest of the international community is to support
our friends in Israel and the Palestinians," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Syrian peace track, Abdullah said that Syria's
new President Bashar al-Assad needs time before resuming peace
talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The president is focused on many issues in his country, but as
he said before, the peace process was started by his late father
and is one that he is willing to continue," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
"We think we just have to give him the time...When he is in a
position or a situation, and this part of the world seems ready...
we hope that he will be ready as a good element in any peace
process," he added.
</P>
<P>
While Barak held talks with Abdullah, Israel's acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami met with his Jordanian counterpart Abdel
Ilah Khatib in a nearby room, to discuss the ways for further
strengthening the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan has a very important interest in this peace process and
we are vary happy to include our Jordanian friends in the situation
of the political process, take note of their sensitivities and
concepts, and see to what extent they can help toward progress,"
Ben-Ami told reporters before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Khatib said Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is determined to
achieve progress and work with Barak in order to conclude a peace
agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Also in the Defense Ministry, Regional Cooperation Minister
Shimon Peres hosted delegations of Israeli and Jordanian political
and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that at the Defense Ministry, we are
talking not about the military matters, but about cooperations,"
Peres said.
</P>
<P>
In Ramallah, Abdullah held talks with Arafat on the issues of
peace process.
</P>
<P>
This was Abdullah's second visit to Israel. He last visited
Israel's southern Red Sea seaport city of Eilat in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
