<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. "Convert Spy" Pressured to Leave Israel: Attorney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jeremiah Mattysse, the American
intelligence officer reported missing from his Texas base and was
later found in Israel, left the country Tuesday aboard an Israeli
flight bound for New York.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the U.S. embassy in Israel said that after speaking
by phone with his seniors at the base, Mattysse decided to return
to the United States, Israel Radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. ambassador Martin Indyk urged Mattysse, a 50-year-
old Christian-turned Judaist, to fly back to the U.S., saying that
he would be treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse was a former commander in a U.S. army unit that trained
intelligence experts and he reportedly had access to classified
information of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA).
</P>
<P>
Israeli police spokesman was also quoted by Israel Radio as
saying that the officer in question had left "on his own free will"
in order to sort out his affair in the U.S. and then come back to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the official claims, Mattysse's attorney Yoram
Sheftel held that the officer had left under strong pressure.
</P>
<P>
"He was kidnapped by the police," Sheftel told the Internet
edition of the leading Israeli daily The Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse has filed an application for Israeli immigrant status
with the Israeli Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Sheftel said it makes no sense that only five or six days after
applying for Israeli citizenship, Mattysse would get up and leave
the country willingly.
</P>
<P>
The attorney said Mattysse was detained Monday evening at a
youth hostel in Mitzpe Ramon in the southern desert area of Negev
and was interrogated until after midnight.
</P>
<P>
When he left the international crimes unit of the police in
Petah Tikva near the coastal city of Tel Aviv, he was in good
spirit and smiled in front of reporters, Sheftel said.
</P>
<P>
During the interrogation he was forced to meet with an unknown
official from the U.S. embassy and kept away from all reporters and
was not permitted to meet with his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse was kept in detention for the legal six hours and then
released, but five hours later he disappeared and was brought back
to the serious crimes department of the police for further
interrogation.
</P>
<P>
At that point, it seemed that he broke down and was quickly sent
in an unmarked civilian vehicle with plainclothes escorts to Ben-
Gurion Airport in Tel Aviv where he was placed on a plane to the U.
S., Sheftel said.
</P>
<P>
Sheftel said it is absurd to say that Mattysse left willingly.
He believed that Mattysse will be tried in a U.S. military court
for desertion and may be sentenced to a number of years in prison.
He is not suspected of passing classified information or spying for
Israel, Sheftel added.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse disappeared on August 7 and then mysteriously turned up
in Israel. He was said to have made his way into the country via
Cyprus under a fake passport.
</P>
<P>
The United States asked Israel to help search for him after his
Israeli girlfriend, Rivka Nir, confirmed his arrival in Israel. It
was also Nir who tipped off the Israeli police about his
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
The woman also claimed that Mattysse had come to Israel with
secret documents.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse has dissociated himself from Nir, saying that the
statements she made about him were false.
</P>
<P>
"I am not a spy. I never passed on any classified information,"
Mattysse earlier told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
