<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Swiss Using Internet on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of people in the
German-speaking part of Switzerland using the Internet has
increased sharply, according to a new survey published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey estimates that around 1.65 million people in the
German-speaking part of Switzerland use the Internet daily, either
for work or private purposes, or both. Eighty-five percent of the
whole country's 7.1 million population speak German.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the Internet users in the German-speaking
part have done on-line shopping. The survey found that there was a
10 percent increase over the past year in the number of on-line
purchases, with 90,000 people confident enough to click their way
through cyber-shopping aisles.
</P>
<P>
Over half of all items bought via the Internet are books. The
second most popular items are CDs, accounting for 43 percent of on-
line sales. The Internet is also a popular tool for making hotel
reservations, which account for 27 percent of all on-line
financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
While Internet-usage is gaining ground, one fifth of all German-
speaking Swiss profess to have no interest in e-commerce,
according to the survey. Around 760,000 Internet-users have never
bought anything over the web, and half of those say they never
will. However, some 42 percent of them said they expected to buy
something on-line within a year.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the Internet users surveyed said they had no
problem communicating their personal data over the web to a
company they deemed reputable.
</P>
<P>
Search engines also proved popular, with 86 percent of Internet-
users saying that they use these sites regularly. Electronic mail
is also very popular. Ninety-six percent of cyber-surfers use the
E-mail service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
