<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Court to Demand More CIA Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Judges at the
Lockerbie trial that resumed on Tuesday demanded the United States
intelligence service to reveal more information.
</P>
<P>
Presiding Judge Lord Ranald lain Sutherland said that chief
prosecutor Colin Boyd must encourage the U.S. secret service to
release potentially relevant cable communications from its agents.
</P>
<P>
Cable communications from American secret service agents in
Malta to Washington were challenged on Tuesday at the Lockerbie
trial as it resumed after a three-week summer recess.
</P>
<P>
The defense team asked the prosecution to provide cable
communications in their entity as it argued that the version sent
to the defense team had been edited with sections and words
blanked out.
</P>
<P>
Defense Counsel William Taylor told the Scottish court on Dutch
soil that he had been informed that the cables, between United
States security service agents in Malta and Washington after
interviews with a Libyan defector, had been edited because they
contained sensitive or irrelevant information.
</P>
<P>
"I emphatically do not accept that what lies behind the blanked-
out sections is of no relevance to a cross-examiner," said Taylor.
</P>
<P>
The cables are introduced by the prosecution to serve as key
evidence in its case against Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin
Khalifa Fahima who are accused of planting a bomb on board of Pan
Am Flight 103.
</P>
<P>
The mid-air explosion on board Pan Am Flight 103 on December 21,
1988, killed 259 people on the New York-bound airliner and 11
others on the ground in the Scottish town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
The cables contained information about the interviews with
Abdul Majid Giaka, a Libyan secret agent who defected shortly
before the Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan defector was scheduled to appear in court to testify
behind a screen with his voice disguised about what he knows about
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors have planned to introduce a batch of cable
communications that combined with the appearance of Giaka in court
is expected to serve as key evidence in the case against the two
Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie trial, that took almost 12 years to investigate
and prepare, finally went underway on May 3 this year and is now
expected to last up to a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
