<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Thanks Swiss Counterpart for Holocaust Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton has thanked his Swiss counterpart Adolf Ogi for helping to
resolve claims relating to Holocaust era assets in Swiss banks,
according to a Swiss Radio International report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed on August 9 to the Swiss president
Clinton praised Swiss banks for compensating Holocaust victims and
their heirs. "With your support, we have reached a historic point
in the Holocaust assets issue," Clinton told Ogi in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that Clinton's letter may signal an end to the
strained relations between Berne and Washington over the issue of
dormant Holocaust-era accounts in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
The letter comes after US district judge, Edward Korman,
approved a 1.25-billion-U.S. dollar settlement between Switzerland
's two biggest banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, and Jewish
organizations over missing assets from the Nazi era. Under the
terms of the settlement, the two Swiss banks will not be liable
for any future claims over dormant accounts.
</P>
<P>
The settlement is compensation for assets that Jews deposited
in Switzerland during the Nazi era. After the Second World War,
many of the account holders have complained that they were unable
to claim their assets. Nearly 600,000 people have said they are
considering making claims for money from the settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
