<HEADLINE> Canada's No. 1 Wireless Supplier to Be Created with 6.6 Billion Cdn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Telus Corp. is taking the biggest
deal of 6.6 billion Canadian dollars (about 4.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in Canadian telecommunications history with an
acquisition of Toronto's Clearnet Communications.
</P>
<P>
The deal creates a Calgary-based new company, Telus Mobility,
which will be the country's No. 1 supplier of wireless services by
revenue, ahead of BCE Inc.'s Bell Mobility and Rogers AT&AMP;T, the
western phone company announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The transaction involves 4.6 billion Canadian dollars (about 3.
1 billion U.S. dollars) in cash and shares, as well as 2 billion
dollars (about 1.4 billion U.S. dollars) in debt assumption.
</P>
<P>
The new company is estimated to have more than 1.8 million
wireless customers with 30.7 million potential subscribers and a
yearly revenue of 1.5 billion dollars (about 1 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
