<HEADLINE> Kenyan Boxer Dreams of Gold in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- George Odindo, Kenya's light-
heavyweight boxer, wants to emulate the late Robert Wangila by
bringing home a gold medal from Sydney, local media reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wangila was the first Kenyan and African to ever win an Olympic
boxing gold medal during the 1988 Seoul Games. Odindo said it was
Wangila's gold that inspired his boxing career.
</P>
<P>
Odindo, the captain of Kenya's four-member boxing team for the
forthcoming Olympic Games in Sydney, said in a recent interview
that "I want to win a gold medal in Sydney and dedicate it to my
parents and son, Reagan. I am tired of living in the shadows of
Cuban and Russian boxers."
</P>
<P>
Just before he flew out to Adelaide, Australia, for
acclimatization, Odindo reiterated that he and his colleagues
would go flat out to restore the country's glory.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Odindo and his twin brother, Samuel Opiyo (
heavyweight), donned national team colors for the first time in
1997 after winning the Kenya Open Championships in the capital
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
He won a light-heavyweight gold medal during the Africa Zone
Five Championships in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, in April this year,
and grabbed another in the Kabaka Mutebi International Tournament
in Kampala, Uganda, in July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
