<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Japan to Promote Economic Relations By Bai Jingshan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- India and Japan are all set to
embark on a new and closer economic relationship with the visit by
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori indicating that he would
present a package during his talks Wednesday with Indian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mori, who arrived here Tuesday evening for a three-day official
visit from Bangalore, 2000 kilometers south of here, is scheduled
to hold wide-ranging talks with his Indian counterpart Atal Biheri
Vajpayee on regional, international and issues of mutual concern,
Indian Foreign Secretary Lalit Mansingh said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first by a Japanese Prime Minister in the last
ten year, highlighted that Tokyo is keen to bring back on track
bilateral relations derailed in the aftermath of India's nuclear
tests in May, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure to New Delhi, the Japanese leader, who
arrived in Bangalore Monday evening from Pakistan, reportedly
proposed a major promotion and cooperation initiative between the
two countries in information technology (IT) sector.
</P>
<P>
Addressing captains of Indian industry and trade in the
southern Indian city, Mori said the initiative would include
training program for 1,000 Indian engineers in Japanese business
practices and language and an Indo-Japan IT summit.
</P>
<P>
A large scale economic mission and a mission of Japanese small
and medium scale enterprises would visit the South Asian country
in October and next January to trigger "active inter-changes" with
promising IT companies, Mori added.
</P>
<P>
Mori said his government was about to launch an "expansive
measure" on the issuance of multiple entry visas for short-stay
visits in Japan from India for business purposes.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese leader spoke of India's high software technology,
saying extraordinary strong complementary relations existed
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He told the Indian industrial leaders that the current
cooperation between the two countries in the IT field still
remained low profile compared to its potential, adding that he
would like to show Indian Prime Minister Vajpayee the proposed IT
promotion and cooperation exchange.
</P>
<P>
Japan is a major source of development assistance and leading
trade partner and investor in India, with the two-way trade
increasing to 4.56 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Japan imposed strict economic sanctions against New Delhi
immediately after India's nuclear tests in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure to India, Mori appealed to India and
neighboring Pakistan to sigh the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (
CTBT) to establish peace in South Asia as a precondition to lift
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
However, a high-ranking Indian official said on Monday that
there was no linkage between lifting of the economic sanctions and
the signing of CTBT by New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Mori flew in Bangalore from Islamabad after his day-long trip
to Pakistan as part of his four-nation tour which includes
Bangladesh, Pakistan, India and Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
