<HEADLINE> Chechnya Elects New Russian State Duma Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chechen Election Commission
announced Tuesday that retired General Aslanbek Aslakhanov has
been elected deputy of the Russian State Duma (lower house of
parliament), according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Aslakhanov, president of the Association of Law Enforcement
Officers of Russia, received 31 percent of the votes, leading his
strongest rival Adam Deniyev, leader of the Humanity movement, who
received 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of registered voters came to polling stations
during Sunday's elections, the Chechen Election Committee Chief
Kerim Arsakhanov said.
</P>
<P>
The elections in Chechnya demonstrate a renewal of the
political situation in the republic, said Viktor Kazantsev,
Russian presidential representative in the southern federal
district.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the elections have taken place indicates a new
turn in developments in Chechnya. Regardless of the threats made
by rebels, or the attempted bribery and intimidation of electoral
commission members and ordinary people, more than 50 percent of
the voters participated in the polls," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The election displays a new distribution of forces in Chechnya,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
With the election of Aslakhanov into the Duma, the Chechens
have chosen to live within Russia and by Russian laws, Kazantsev
said.
</P>
<P>
The voting began at 8 a.m. Moscow time (0400 GMT) Sunday in all
of Chechnya's 19 electoral districts, including the Shatoi, Itum-
Kale and Vedeno mountainous districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
