<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwegians Leave Submarine, Russians Vow to Continue Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Moscow on Tuesday vowed to carry
on the search of the sunken nuclear submarine "Kursk," despite the
fact that Norwegian divers who participated in the previous
investigation have left the disaster area.
</P>
<P>
A correspondent from the Russian RTR, the only television
company allowed by the Russian navy to work aboard the cruiser "
Pyotr Velikiy" (the Great Peter) in the disaster area and report
on the rescue operations, said the Norwegian decision to leave
stems from the fact that their contract has ended.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian divers arrived to help save the crew, but they cannot
get involved in a search for the dead. They reportedly do not
have a license for this, and it requires very thorough
preparations, the correspondent explained. He added that it is
not known how the situation will develop in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Russia had earlier been expected to make arrangements with the
Norwegian deep-sea divers to recover the dead 118-member crew. "
The Russian side has taken on commitments to conclude a contract
and pay the expenses for doing this hazardous work," Russia's
Northern Fleet Chief of Staff Mikhail Motsak told the RTR.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the General Staff Admiral Viktor Kravchenko told
Interfax that the navy's supreme commander has ordered the search
to continue until the last seaman's body is recovered from the
submarine.
</P>
<P>
"This order will unquestionably be carried out," and "any
difficulties will be overcome," Kravchenko pledged, adding that "
the Northern Fleet's rescue forces and equipment are still working
in the area." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
