<HEADLINE> South Korean Economy Grows 9.6 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean economy grew 9.6
percent in the second quarter of this year compared with the same
period last year, the Bank of Korea said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the growth to increased facility
investments and export.
</P>
<P>
Facility investment rose 41.3 percent, and consumption in the
private sector climbed 9 percent while merchandise exports soared
23.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic and overseas demand for industrial
machinery, computers and semiconductors was brisk, leading to a 16.
8 percent growth in manufacturing sector output.
</P>
<P>
However, the consumption and construction investments were
comparatively small. The bank ruled out concern over excessive
consumption.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over the economy have been widespread due to financial
market jitters caused by a credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth clearly indicates that the economy has been
functioning well, said a bank spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
