<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechnya Elects New Russian State Duma Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chechen Election Commission
announced Tuesday that retired General Aslanbek Aslakhanov has won
a seat in the Russian State Duma, the lower house of parliament,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Aslakhanov, president of the Association of Law Enforcement
Officers of Russia, received 31 percent of the votes, leading his
closest rival, Adam Deniyev, leader of Humanity movement, by 12
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The republic's administration head Akhmad Kadyrov
congratulated the winner and said the next stage election for the
administration head should be held no later than a year from now.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of registered voters came to polling stations
for Sunday's elections, the Chechen Election Committee Chief Kerim
Arsakhanov said.
</P>
<P>
The elections in Chechnya demonstrate a renewal of the
political situation in the republic, Viktor Kazantsev, Russian
presidential representative in the southern federal district, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the elections have taken place indicates that a
new turn has taken place in the developments in Chechnya.
Regardless of the threats made by rebels, the attempted bribery
and intimidation of electoral commission members and ordinary
people, more than 50 percent of the voters participated in the
polls," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The elections display a new distribution of forces in
Chechnya," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Bearing in mind that the administration led by Akhmad Kadyrov
has come to exist, and the population of Chechnya now has a
representative in the federal legislature, it can be said that
residents of the republic have chosen to live within Russia and by
Russian laws," Kazantsev said.
</P>
<P>
The voting began at 8 a.m. Moscow time (0400 GMT) Sunday in
all of Chechnya's 19 electoral districts, including the Shatoi,
Sharoi, Itum-Kale and Vedeno mountain districts.
</P>
<P>
There were 495,000 people registered as official voters.
Thirteen candidates ran for the parliament seat, among them
Aslakhanov, Deniyev, leader of the local branch of the Unity
movement Lecha Magamadov and former Chechen parliamentary Chairman
Amin Osmayev.
</P>
<P>
Unprecedented measures to prevent terrorist attacks were in
place. Following a recent series of attacks against polling
stations, road traffic has been restricted. The authorities have
urged citizens to refrain from traveling outside their immediate
areas.
</P>
<P>
The elections were declared valid as voter turnout surpassed
25 percent, which is needed by law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
