<HEADLINE> Canadian Company to Strike Transit System Deal in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bombardier Inc., Canada's
aerospace and rail transportation equipment maker, is close to a
deal worth 438 million Canadian dollars (about 297 million U.S.
dollars) to help build a rapid transit system in South Korea, the
National Post newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal-based company and Kumho Industrial Co., Ltd. will
be the leading members of the consortium for the project worth 1.6
billion Canadian dollars (about 1.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Other partners include Lotte Engineering &AMP; Construction Co.
Ltd., Iljin Electric Co. Ltd. and Econ International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Bombardier expects to finalize the terms of the contract by the
first quarter of next year and begin construction by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Bombardier will be responsible for the core electrical and
mechanical systems, including the initial 46 vehicles, for the
fully automated line that will link Kimhae with Pusan in the
southern tip of the Korean peninsula. 
</P>
