<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Abdullah Visits Israel EDS-1st lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Abdullah II
arrived in Tel Aviv on Tuesday for talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak on the Middle East peace process and ways to
improve relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah and his party were greeted at Tel Aviv's Sde Dov
Airport by Barak and other senior Israeli government and military
officials.
</P>
<P>
In his welcome address, Barak said Abdullah's visit to Israel "
is another milestone in the relationship between Israel and Jordan
which was climaxed in 1994 by the signing of the peace treaty
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The king's visit came at a time when Israel's peace negotiations
with the Palestinians are at a critical stage and will no doubt
help move this peace process forward, he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak promised that his government is determined to continue to
seek peace in the Middle East, particularly with all of Israel's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks, Barak
said it is time for both the Israeli and Palestinian leaders to
make "painful decisions" so that a peace agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
Barak urged Abdullah to play a greater role in helping Israel
reach peace agreements with the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Jordan is committed to helping realize peace in
the region and will continue to help the parties concerned find
reasonable solutions to the Middle East problems.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian people have been fighting for their fundamental
rights for a long time and such rights should be recognized in
settling the Israeli-Palestinian issue, the king added.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Israel to continue its efforts to reach peace with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
This was the second meeting between Abdullah and Barak in about
a week. After the welcoming ceremony, Abdullah and Barak were
driven to the Defense Ministry in the city for a working meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the way, Abdullah stopped at the Rabin Square to lay a wreath
at the site of the assassination of late Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin. The late premier was shot and killed in 1995 by a Jewish
extremist who opposed his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah last visited Israel in April in the southern Red Sea
port city of Eilat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
