<HEADLINE> Manila Claims to Continue Peace Talks with MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks will continue between
the Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
MILF) panels the chief government negotiator said in Mindandao on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Edgardo Batenga, government chief negotiator made the
announcement in a radio interview in Cotabato city of Maguindanao
province following the decision by the MILF central committee to
stop its peace negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Batenga said he is hopeful that through back channel
communications, he could still convince the MILF panels to return
to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
He, however, clarified that despite the disbandment of the MILF
peace panel, the plan of the government would remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The other day, Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military
affairs, announced in a press statement that the central committee
has decommissioned the MILF peace panel and all its staff members.
</P>
<P>
The recall of authority, according to Murad, was issued by MILF
Chairman Hashim Salamat on August 14 in what they see as the
government's "insincerity" in pursuing a peaceful resolution of
the armed conflict in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Salamat, according to Murad, described as "absurd" the
government preconditions on the resumption of talks and the bounty
offered for the arrest of top MILF leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The central committee," Murad said, "could not tolerate
risking the safety of the MILF panel members, advisers,
consultants, staff members and the working groups in the face of
the arrest warrants."
</P>
<P>
As a "goodwill" gesture, however, President Joseph Estrada has
ordered Interior Secretary Alfredo Lim the other day to withdraw
the bounty offered for the arrest of Salamat, Murad, and MILF
spokesman Eid Kabalu. 
</P>
