<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Money Changers Suggest Auction Sale of Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi money changers Tuesday
suggested reintroduction of "auction sale" of foreign currency to
check underground transfer and encourage official inflow of
foreign remittance to raise the country's poor foreign exchange
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's Foreign exchange reserve was 2.03 billion U.S.
dollars when the present government assumed power in 1996, then it
came down to 1.62 billion dollars in May this year and 1.4 billion
by now, Bangladesh Money Changers Association (BMCA) president
Kefayet Ullah Masud told a press conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reintroduction of auction system remains the only option to
raise the foreign exchange reserve to a safe level, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Masud said foreign currencies remitted by non-resident
Bangladeshis (NRBs were sold in open auction at competitive prices,
which encouraged them to remit money only through the official
channel till June, 1984.
</P>
<P>
The then government later stopped the system and introduced
bank-fixed exchange rates, encouraging underground transaction
which offers NRBs better rates and now controls 70 to 80 percent
inflow of foreign remittance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign remittance inflow in the 1999-2000 fiscal year amounted
to about 1.9 billion dollars, of which 40 to 45 percent came from
Saudi Arabia alone, he informed.
</P>
<P>
Frequent devaluation would never help increase inward
remittance through official channel, as underground traders always
offer higher rate than the official one, Masud said, decrying the
government's logic that devaluation would help increase foreign
exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
The government recently announced the devaluation of the
currency by 6 percent to 54 taka against one dollar, aiming to
remain competitive in the world market and increase foreign
exchange reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
