<HEADLINE> No Recovery of "Kursk" Expected Before Autumn of 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The sunken Russian nuclear
submarine "Kursk" cannot be raised from the Barents Sea floor
before autumn of next year, a senior Russian naval officer said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It will take at least three or four months to recover the
submarine if the work begins in May," Admiral Eduard Baltin, a
former commander of Russia's Black Sea Fleet said in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Regarding statements by the general contractor from the Rubin
Design Bureau, which claimed the Kursk could be brought up by the
beginning of winter, Baltin said it's "a theory, not a
practicality."
</P>
<P>
To place a sling under the submarine requires at least three
trenches being dug under it, the admiral said. According to his
experience, strong currents, which could reach 2.5 knots in the
area, would destroy the trenches. High-pressure equipment would
have to be in use constantly to support them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
