<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biodiversity Farming Helps China Combat Rice Blast, Up Yields (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The results of Chinese field
trials have reinforced the accepted scientific wisdom that
planting different varieties of a crop in the same field
suppresses the spread of certain diseases and improves yields.
</P>
<P>
Li Yan, one of the researchers in the program, said today in a
telephone interview with Xinhua that the large-scale experiments
conducted during 1998 and 1999 are unprecedented in the world.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Professor Zhu Youyong, a plant pathologist at the
Phytopathology Laboratory at Yunnan Agricultural University in
Kunming, southwest China, a research team found an 18 percent rise
in overall productivity, including greater profits for a premium-
priced variety that is particularly susceptible to rice blast from
a fungus.
</P>
<P>
The experiments involved mixing two varieties of rice in the
same field at 10 townships in the province, covering 4,000 ha.
</P>
<P>
Farmers planted a single row of glutinous rice in the middle
of a group of either four or six rows of hybrid rice. The
experiment started on 812 ha in 1998 and expanded to 3,342 ha in
1999. Monoculture control plots were grown at 15 small sites
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the results, it would take an average of 1.18
hectares of monoculture cropland to produce the same amounts of
hybrid and glutinous rice produced in one hectare of mixed crops.
</P>
<P>
The most striking change was for individual glutinous plants
grown in a mixed environment. They yielded up to 89 percent more
rice than their monocultural cousins.
</P>
<P>
Li said as the glutinous rice fetches at a premium price, the
value per hectare of the mixed fields was 14 percent greater than
the hybrid monoculture plots and 40 percent greater than the
glutinous monoculture plots.
</P>
<P>
In both years, blast destroyed about 20 percent of the
glutinous rice grain in the monoculture plots but only one percent
in the mixed plots. Blast damage in the hybrid rice, although much
lower in general, also dropped, with a grain loss of only one
percent in the mixed plots as opposed to 2.3 percent in
monoculture plots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NW City Boosts Cultural Relics Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TURPAN (XINJIANG), August 22 (Xinhua) -- An important city on
the world famous "Silk Road", Turpan is making efforts to further
improve the protection of its cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The city of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
has five key cultural relic sites at the country level and other
23 sites at the provincial level, including the Thousand-Buddha
Grottoes, the Astana Ancient Tombs and the Jiaohe Ancient City
Ruins.
</P>
<P>
The local bureau of cultural relics has invested 400,000 yuan
to build a 150-meter-long anti-flood facility along the Jiaohe
ruins, which are only 30 meters away from a river.
</P>
<P>
Safety devices such as aluminum alloy doors and vitreous
balusters are set up in the Thousand-Buddha Grottoes and other
cultural relics to better protect the grottoes and the valuable
frescoes.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city invested over two million yuan in 1,
000-square-meter hall of huge rhinoceros fossils in the Turpan
Museum.
</P>
<P>
Turpan Basin, a desert area in northwest China, is deemed by
some as "the world's richest open archeological museum". Almost 80
per cent of the cultural relics in the region's museums came from
Turpan.
</P>
<P>
Turpan's rich cultural heritage has attract tourists to the
small city, said Yue Feng, director of the Xinjiang Cultural
Relics Administration.
</P>
<P>
Over 500,000 domestic and foreign tourists visited the city
last year, according to local statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
