<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to
grow by 4.4 percent in the second quarter of 2000, compared with a
1.7 percent contraction in the second quarter of 1999, reported
Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's GDP contracted by a record 6.4 percent in 1999, caused
by the aftermath of two devastating earthquakes in the country's
heavily industrialized northwest late in the year, and the Russian
and Asian financial crises in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The GDP expanded 5.6 percent in the first quarter of this year
and experts are foreseeing the year-end GDP to grow at 5-5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
JEDDAH -- A consortium, formed by Saudi, Canadian, German and
Austrian companies, plans to bid for building a new railway line in
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The consortium, led by Saudi and Canadian companies, will submit
the relevant offer to the Communications Ministry later next month
to build the projected line, which sets off from northern Quryiat
to Hail then Qasim, and Riyadh before it terminates at the Red Sea
port city of Jeddah in the east.
</P>
<P>
If the consortium secures the project, the construction
operation will start from a line linking Damam and Jubail where
Saudi oil industry is mainly located. And the 3,000-kilometer line
would be completed in phases under set schedule.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility studies showed that the proposed line was of great
economic value as it would help transport mining and farm products
from the northern areas to the processing and communal zones in the
east.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The world's giant companies refuse to let private
Turkish airlines lease planes from them anymore because Turkey's
civil aviation sector is suffering from a terrible image problem,
reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 private aviation companies have been set up in recent
years but only seven have survived. The bankrupt companies failed
to make payments for the planes they have leased.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the state-run Turkish Airlines (THY) said that
the "embargo" will not affect THY, adding that those foreign
companies are trying to seize the Turkish market by imposing the
embargo on private Turkish companies.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Morocco officially announced that it has discovered an
abundant amount of oil and natural gas in its territories,
promising enough to turn the country from importer to producer of
energy.
</P>
<P>
King Mohammad VI on Sunday announced at the Youth Festival
gathering that "Morocco has discovered abundant good quality oil
and gas in Talisint, Fekik province."
</P>
<P>
That was the first official announcement on finding oil in
Morocco since U.S. companies launched prospection operations at the
areas bordering Algeria three months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
