<HEADLINE> Jordan Firmly Opposes Israeli Control Over Jerusalem: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel
Ilah al-Khatib on Tuesday reaffirmed his country's firm opposition
to the Israeli control over the disputed holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib told reporters after the talks between Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and visiting Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein in the West bank city of Ramallah on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib who accompanied Abdullah in the visit reiterated that
his country rejected any Israeli sovereignty over Jerusalem which
is a Palestinian territory under the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's trip came within the continued co-ordination and
consultation between the Palestinian and Jordanian sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
This was the monarch's third visit to the Palestinian
territories
since he assumed power in February 1999 succeeding his late father
King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah left for Tel Aviv later in the day, which is his
second visit to Israel, for talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak. 
</P>
