<HEADLINE> Singapore Newspaper Group Sets up TV News Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 22 (Xinhua)-- The Singapore Press Holding
Limited (SPH), the country's sole newspaper publisher, Tuesday
announced the setting up of two TV News units, paving the way for
the group's move into the broadcasting medium with the launch of
two TV channels to be run by its subsidiary SPH MediaWorks and
scheduled to go on air next year.
</P>
<P>
Leading editors from SPH newspapers told a press conference
Tuesday that one of the TV News units is subordinated to SPH's
English and Malay Newspapers Division (EMND) and the other is
within its Chinese Newspapers Division (CND).
</P>
<P>
They said the SPH TV News units will produce and supply news
and current affairs programs to the TV channels by leveraging on
the strong pool of journalistic resources and content produced by
SPH newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The key strategy adopted by SPH in its approach to TV News is
to build up a core team of broadcast journalists, supported and
linked to the wider resources of the EMND and CND newsrooms, they
added.
</P>
<P>
Two veterans, experienced in TV newsroom environment, have been
posted as editors to head the TV News units respectively and
printing journalists will benefit from their wealth of TV news
experience to cross over between news reporting for print as well
as TV.
</P>
<P>
Lim Jim Koon, Editor of Lianhe Zaobao, Singapore's leading
newspaper in Chinese language, said SPH is the first newspaper
publisher that operates TV channels at least in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Leslie Fong, Editor of Straits Times, the country's leading
English newspaper, expressed his confidence that leveraging on the
paper's existing journalistic talent will give SPH the competitive
edge in its TV News coverage.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Television Corporation of Singapore (TCS) and
Singapore Television of Singapore Pte Ltd (STV12) operate a total
of four channels and the Singapore Cable Vision Ltd (SCV) provides
cable TV services.
</P>
<P>
As the launch of SPH's two TV channels will bring to six the
total of TV channels in Singapore and the government has given the
TCS licenses to publish two newspapers, and competition in the
country's medium is expected to become more tense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
