<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Prevent Chinese Tourists From Being Cheated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will step up efforts to
prevent Chinese tourists from being cheated by so called "zero-
dollar tours", Adisai Bodharamik, Minister to the Prime Minister's
Office and Chairman of the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT)
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Adisai, who just came back from a two-day meeting of top
tourism officials of China, Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore in
China, said, "Thailand is fully supporting concrete measures to
solve the problem of Chinese tourists getting unfair tour programs.
"
</P>
<P>
The problem of "zero-dollar tours", he said, is now very common
in Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore, in which the Chinese tourists
pay a very low price for a tour program but have to suffer through
illegal activities like soliciting prostitutes, gambling or being
taken to shopping to generate kickbacks to the tourist guides.
</P>
<P>
"That is why the top tourism officials of the four countries
met in China," he said, noting the four sides have agreed in a
memorandum of understanding that they will use strict measures to
punish the tour operators who conducted "zero-dollar tours" or
other illegal activities to Chinese tourists.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, the tour operator in one of the four countries
will be immediately taken off the list of certified trading
partners in other three countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that under the memorandum of understanding, tour
companies must guarantee that the cost per tourist in a program
must not fall below 18 U.S. dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
Adisai said he will soon call a meeting of all Thai tour
companies that handle Chinese tour groups to crack down illegal
tourism activities to Chinese tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Customs Duties Boost Car Imports in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sales of imported cars in
Romania, boosted by lower customs duties on imports from the
European Union (EU), doubled in the first half of this year, the
local daily newspaper Ziarul Financiar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's customs duties on EU cars dropped to 12 percent
from 30 percent on January 1 this year. The duties are scheduled
to be cut by another 6 percent as of January 1, 2001, and will be
completely abolished beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons for Romania's increase in car imports include the
expanded leasing system, lower car prices, and the cancellation of
the 5 percent road tax charged on new vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Romanians have a preference for European-made cars, and they
purchase cars that cost 8,000 to 12,000 U.S. dollars, according to
experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
