<HEADLINE> Pakistan Accuses Britain of Not Helping in Anti-Graft Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Tuesday accused
Britain of failing to help trace people accused of corruption
against the government of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pervez Musharaf, chairman of Pakistan's joint chiefs of staff
committee, speaking from Pakistan in a BBC radio interview, said
that his government believed a number of people suspected of graft
were living in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan had passed a list of 14 names to the British
Home Office, but Britain failed to help trace them.
</P>
<P>
"These are the people who have looted and plundered this poor
country and we thought we would get some assistance in getting
them back, or at least getting information on them, but I'm afraid
the Home Office was not forthcoming," Musharaf said in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
"I feel that the money they have looted may not make the
United Kingdom much richer, but it certainly makes Pakistan poorer,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
Many on the list are linked to former Pakistani prime
ministers Nawaz Sharif, who is now serving a jail sentence, and
Benazir Bhutto, who has been living in London for a year while
fighting a corruption conviction in Pakistan, BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
Denying the accusation, British Foreign Office Minister Peter
Hain said that Britain was ready to assist with Pakistan's anti-
corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Britain could act only when the Pakistani
authorities transferred "a proper international arrest warrant for
these individuals." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
