<HEADLINE> Final Negotiations Reached For Major Sino-Foreign Ethylene Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Final negotiations have been
reached for launching a major Sino-foreign ethylene project in
Huizhou in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Local governmental sources said preparations for the joint
venture between the China National Offshore Oil Corp.(CNOOC),
Guangdong Province and Shell International Chemical Co. Ltd. were
expected to be finished in October. A formal contract for the
joint venture will be signed by late October.
</P>
<P>
The ethylene project was formally approved by the China's
central government in December 1997. Huizhou was chosen as the
location of the project.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project will be 4.3 billion U.S. dollars.
A petrochemical joint venture will produce 800,000 tons of
ethylene annually.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the joint venture was first put forward in 1988.
An agreement regarding a feasibility study was signed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
On August 14, Wei Liucheng, general manager of CNOOC, held high-
ranking talks with the CEO of Shell International Chemical Co. Ltd.
regarding remaining contract issues for operation and technical
services. They reached an agreement the following day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
