<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy to South Lebanon Makes First Tour of Blue Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan's newly-appointed representative in south Lebanon Rolf
Knutsson Monday made his first tour of the U.N.-drawn Blue Line
since he arrived in the country, As Safir newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish envoy told reporters at Sheikh Abbad hill, one of
the two border points where his convoy stopped for a field
verification, that his mission was to make sure that U.N. Security
Council Resolutions 425 and 426 had been implemented after Israel
withdrew its troops from south Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Knutsson flew by a U.N. helicopter earlier Monday from Beirut to
the headquarters of the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon
(UNIFIL) at the coastal town of Naqoura, near the border with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy said his mission was also to confirm that the
UNIFIL would carry out its mission of helping the Lebanese
authorities re-establish Lebanon's sovereignty all the way to the
internationally recognized border.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL spokesman Nejib Friji said that UNIFIL commanders briefed
Knutsson on developments along the Blue Line and security condition
in the area.
</P>
<P>
Knutsson, a former UNIFIL senior advisor, then inspected a
platoon of Nepalese soldiers at Marwahine, a border point, and met
a unit of Finnish peacekeepers at Khiam.
</P>
<P>
This is Knutsson's first trip since he arrived in Lebanon on
August 16.
</P>
<P>
Knutsson was appointed by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan as a
diplomatic and political liaison with the Lebanese government to
oversee the implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolutions 425
and 426.
</P>
<P>
Knutsson will serve for an initial period of six months, during
which he will also supervise reconstruction efforts in the south.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, As Safir newspaper reported that the Israeli army had
set up a belt of ground-to-air missiles along the eastern sector of
the border with Lebanon, opposite to the Shabaa Farms district in
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
The belt was established with a claimed aim of intercepting any
Katyusha rockets fired by Hezbollah guerrillas into northern Israel
in the future.
</P>
<P>
At least 16 Israeli missiles spreading over four batteries could
be seen facing the region, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
