<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. "Convert Spy" Ready to Leave Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jeremiah Mattysse, the American
intelligence officer reported missing from his Texas base and found
in Israel, has decided to return to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse, the so-called "convert spy", is being questioned by
police in Petah Tikva, near the coastal city of Tel Aviv and has
agreed to leave Israel out of his own will, said Israel Radio
reports on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The officer, who was located Monday by Israeli police detectives
in a hostel in the southern desert town of Mitzpeh Ramon, was taken
to police headquarters in Petah Tikva without resistance.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse, 50, served as a senior intelligence officer in the U.
S. Army and had access to top-secret information. Three weeks ago,
he went on vacation and failed to return to duty when his leave
expired.
</P>
<P>
The officer, who converted to Judaism, made his way to Israel
and has applied for Israeli immigrant status.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a lot of information about him came from his self-
styled girlfriend, Rivka Nir, who once hinted that Mattysse had
been spying for Israel and brought with him several bags of secret
information.
</P>
<P>
Mattysse has dissociated himself from Nir, saying that she made
statements about him that were false.
</P>
<P>
"I am not a spy. I never passed on any classified information,"
Mattysse told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that he had talked to U.S. and Israeli officials
and described his presence in Israel as being on vacation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli police have no legal authority to arrest the
American officer or extradite him to the United States, and have
tried to persuade him to return to his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
