<HEADLINE> No Plan For Permanent Indian Naval Base: Maldives President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Maldives President
Abdul Gayoom said here Tuesday that his country was not
considering any proposal to set up a permanent Indian naval base
in any of its islands.
</P>
<P>
Winding up his two-day official visit to New Delhi, Gayoom
told the press that there was no such proposal and the issue did
not come up during his talks with Indian leaders including Prime
Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
However, Maldives had "excellent levels of cooperation in
defense", he said before his departure for Hyderabad, 1,500
kilometers south of here.
</P>
<P>
Gayoom, who held wide-ranging talks with Vajpayee on Monday,
said that Maldives considered India as a valued friend and
development partner, adding that his visit was aimed at bringing
the two countries closer by further consolidating bonds of
friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The president said on Monday that he supported India's
proposal for a comprehensive international convention against
terrorism scheduled to be taken up at the United Nations General
Assembly session next month.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting between Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee and the Maldives President Abdul Gayoom, who arrived here
on Monday, a spokesman of Indian External Affairs Ministry told
the press that the two sides "articulated their strong common
position against terrorism and fundamentalism".
</P>
<P>
Maldives supported India's initiative on having a
comprehensive international convention against terrorism, he
added.
</P>
<P>
At a banquet hosted in honor of the visiting Maldives
President last evening, Indian President kocheril Raman Narayanan
appealed for a early adoption of a convention on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
India has been supplying defense equipment to Maldives which
has a population of 260,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
