<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Arrives in Ramallah for Pushing Peace Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
arrived in the West Bank city of Ramallah Tuesday for an official
visit to the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who flew in by helicopter, was greeted by Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat, a host of
Palestinian officials and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Abdullah are expected to discuss the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process in the wake of the
failed peace talks at Camp David, the U.S., last month between
Arafat, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are also to tackle ways to push forward the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The monarch will later in the day head for Tel Aviv for a
meeting with Barak, during which he is reportedly to reiterate his
kingdom's dissatisfaction with Israel's control over Jerusalem and
support for Palestinian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East war and declared Jerusalem as its "eternal and indivisible"
capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Currently Jordan is hosting some 1.5 million Palestinian
refugees registered with the United Nations. Amman insists
they should have the rights to choose between returning to their
homeland or staying in the kingdom while asking for compensations
from parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
This is Abdullah's second visit to Israel and his third to the
Palestinian territories since he became Jordan's king in February
1999.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been a major peace broker between Israel and Arab
neighbors since it signed a peace treaty in 1994 with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
