<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Double Oil Imports from Oman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Suwat told reporters that his ministry had submitted a bigger
oil order, increased from 17,000 barrels a day to 34,000 barrels a
day, to Oman's energy ministry through the Omani Embassy to
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil from Oman, a major oil producing country outside the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), is about 10
to 20 cents a barrel cheaper than that of OPEC members, he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from doubling oil import, the Thai government had also
decided to extend its oil contract with Oman, scheduled to expire
in November, for another year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The move was part of the government's efforts to ease
difficulties faced by Thai people due to a continued increase in
gasoline prices over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices are widely expected to rise again Wednesday to a
record level of more than 17 baht (42.5 cents) a liter for premium
gasoline in Greater Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Thailand's five major oil refiners plan
to propose some changes in oil product specifications that may
help arrest soaring oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The changes would increase the production yield from crude at
the cost of slightly relaxed environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Petroleum Authority of Thailand has forced the
partly state-owned Thaioil, which commands the largest share of
the Thai oil market, to reduce the refining margin by one U.S.
dollars a barrel in order to curb pump prices increases.
</P>
<P>
The world oil price is at its highest level in 10 years,
averagely at 31 U.S. Dollars a barrel, and is expected to maintain
at high levels until the end of the year before beginning to
decline, given a maintained oil production level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
