<HEADLINE> Britain Demands Release of TV Crew by Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday demanded the
immediate release by Liberian authorities of a four-man British
television crew, who were indicted for espionage.
</P>
<P>
"It brings the Liberian government into collision course not
just with the United Nations ... over sanctions busting and
support for the rebel forces in Sierra Leone, but now also against
the whole international climate, which favors press freedom,"
Foreign Office minister Peter Hain told BBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
"They are not spies, they are journalists, and this is an
attack on international press freedom."
</P>
<P>
"They should be released forthwith and the charges immediately
withdrawn," said Hain.
</P>
<P>
The two Britons, a Sierra Leonean and a South African were
arrested on Monday when they were working on a documentary for
Britain's Channel Four television.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted legal sources in Liberia as saying that if
convicted, the four, who arrived in the country on August 1, might
face up to 10 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Channel Four said the crew were in Liberia on legitimate
journalistic business and they had been working on a documentary
about how an African country could end a cycle of political
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
