<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Re-Opens After Summer Recess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Cable
communications from intelligence services were challenged at the
Lockerbie trial as it resumed on Tuesday after a three-week summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
The defense team asked the prosecution to provide cable
communications in their entity after it argued that the version
sent to the defense team had been edited with sections and words
blanked out.
</P>
<P>
Defense Counsel William Taylor told the Scottish court on Dutch
soil that he had been informed that the cables, between United
States security service agents and Washington after interviews
with a Libyan defector, had been edited because they contained
sensitive or irrelevant information.
</P>
<P>
"I emphatically do not accept that what lies behind the blanked-
out sections is of no relevance to a cross-examiner," said Taylor.
</P>
<P>
The cables are gathered by the prosecution to serve as key
evidence in its case against Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-Amin
Khalifa Fahima who are accused of planting a bomb on board of Pan
Am Flight 103. The mid-air explosion on December 21, 1988, killed
259 people on the New York-bound airliner and 11 others on the
ground in the Scottish town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
The cables contained information about the interviews with
Abdul Majid Giaka, a Libyan secret agent who defected shortly
before the Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan defector was scheduled to appear in court to testify
behind a screen with his voice disguised about what he knows about
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie trial, that took almost 12 years to investigate
and prepare, finally went underway on May 3 this year and is now
expected to last up to a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Experts to Work on Countering Olympic Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A crack team of computer
experts will be working around the clock at next month's Olympics
to counter a new type of attack - cyber terrorism, a senior
Australian government official said in Sydney on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While computer hackers who change finals results and play
around with medal winners may not be perceived to be as dangerous
as armed terrorists, there is no doubt they could cause havoc and
serious embarrassment for games organisers.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Communications Minister Richard Alston said
before a cabinet meeting that the use of the Internet to disrupt
the Games was being considered a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
The thousands of results from the 39 venues will all be kept in
electronic form and posted on the official Olympic website which
is expected to receive more than one billion hits.
</P>
<P>
Alston said the methods being used to protect the system from
hackers would remain secret.
</P>
<P>
"We are not about to telegraph our punches - but clearly the
important thing is to be acutely aware that you can't take
anything for granted," he said.
</P>
<P>
"You can't assume goodwill, you've got to proceed on the basis
that there will be people trying to cause difficulties and do your
best to avoid those," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
