<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Establish Partnership With OSCE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand wants to become a
partner for cooperation with the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the Thai News Agency (TNA) said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan confirmed the country's
position at a meeting here on Monday with Ambassadors to Bangkok
of 15 member states of the European Union (EU) and representatives
of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs would organize a seminar on
Thailand's cooperation with the OSCE in term of information and
experience exchange here between September 27 and 29 while a
senior Foreign Ministry official would discuss the possibility of
the Thai-OSCE relationship at a meeting in Brussels early next
month, Surin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The partnership of cooperation with the OSCE begins with an
exchange of experiences, and involves some political support on
security issues in the international arena, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea are currently the only Asian countries to
have established partnership with the OSCE, according to Surin.
</P>
</TEXT>
