<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin to Be in Murmansk for Kursk Mourning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
will fly to the city of Severomorsk, near the base of the Northern
Fleet in Murmansk, Tuesday afternoon to attend the memorial
services for the 118 crewmen who died with the sunken nuclear
submarine Kursk, said the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, Putin declared Wednesday a day of national
mourning for the submarine's crew.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of Putin's visit to Severomorsk is to meet
with the families and relatives of the dead, the Interfax news
agency cited the Russian Northern Fleet headquarters as saying.
</P>
<P>
There may be several such meetings, the headquarters said.
Putin is also expected to hold a conference with fleet commanders.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted sources in Severomorsk and Moscow as saying
Putin is not planning to sail to the area in the Barents Sea,
where the submarine went down on August 12.
</P>
<P>
The president is expected to arrive at the Northern Fleet base
late Tuesday. Top defense officials will accompany Putin on his
trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
