<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Supports Syrian FM's Call for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid has reiterated the need to hold an Arab summit and
expressed support for a call made by Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk
Shareh in this regard, Egypt's Al Ahram daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There is "increasing importance to convene a well-prepared Arab
summit" to discuss issues related to the Arab nation, including the
Middle East peace process, Abdel-Meguid said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The latest call made by Shareh in this regard "has reaffirmed
such a need," the chief of the pan-Arab forum was quoted as saying
by the newspaper, which usually mirrors Egyptian government's
views.
</P>
<P>
The request for holding an Arab summit is "natural and
legitimate," he added.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in
Alexandria on Monday, Shareh urged Arab leaders to meet to seek
ways of ending the "wretched situation of disunity" in the Arab
world for the benefit of the Arab nation and the regional peace and
stability. He said this situation must not be allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has expressed
reservations over Shareh's call. Responding to his statement,
Moussa suggested on Monday that Shareh's goals could be
accomplished at a planned meeting of Arab foreign ministers on
September 3 in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Talks between Mubarak and Shareh focused on the need to
coordinate Arab positions on several problems, and both sides
agreed to "look at ways to assure such coordination at the most
efficient level," namely the Arab League's upcoming foreign
ministers meeting, Moussa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
