<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Vietnam to Step Up Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral trade between
Malaysia and Vietnam is expected to grow by 20 percent this year
following renewed interest by businessmen from both sides to step
up trade, Vietnamese ambassador to Malaysia Tran Trong Toan said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There has been a steady stream of Malaysian businessmen
visiting Vietnam and vice-versa looking at opportunities to step
up trade as well as investment, he said at a briefing here on the
economic situation and investment opportunities in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said Malaysian businessmen are very committed
and serious in doing business in Vietnam. "They are highly
appreciated in Vietnam," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between Malaysia and Vietnam amounted to 638
million U.S. dollars last year with Malaysia exporting mainly
chemical products, fertilizers, timber, palm oil and natural
rubber to Vietnam and importing rice, groundnut, cashew nut,
vegetable and aquatic products from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is considering the import of new items such as beef,
poultry, pork, livestock and breeding pigs to help narrow the
trade imbalance with Vietnam, according to the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia is expected to increase import of rice to
150,000 tons this year from 100,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador hoped that with the recovery of the Malaysian
economy, Malaysian investment in Vietnam would increase.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia ranks third among ASEAN countries, next to Singapore
and Thailand, with 70 projects already implemented and 941 million
U.S. dollars already committed.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian investments are mainly concentrated in food
processing plants, textile and garments, banking and the hotel
industry.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is impressed with Malaysia's economic development and
is trying to emulate Malaysia's transformation success from being
agricultural-based economy to industrial based economy, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
