<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Tracking Device for Stolen Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday launched a
new device known as Checkmate to track down stolen cars.
</P>
<P>
The tracking device launched here by its operator Cybertrek (
Malaysia) Sdn Bhd provides a vehicle tracking and recovery service.
</P>
<P>
At the launch, Cybertrek's Chief Executive Officer Naharudin
Ali said the system will be available to the motoring public in
September and the tentative price tag is 2,000 ringgit (526 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that when a car fitted with Checkmate is stolen, the
owner only needs to call into Cybertrek's Control Center and as
soon as the Control Center receives a call reporting a car theft,
the process of tracking will be activated immediately.
</P>
<P>
Simultaneously, the police will be alerted about the incident
and details of the affected vehicle will be transmitted to the
relevant police station.
</P>
<P>
The product comes with a five-year warranty and Cybertrek is
providing a full money-back guarantee should Checkmate fail to
live up to its features.
</P>
<P>
Confident in the product, Naharudin said the company should be
able to sell 20,000 units in the first year alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
