<HEADLINE> Thailand Dismisses Rumors of Late Succession of WTO Head Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's candidate will take
his turn to head the World Trade Organization (WTO) in September
2002, Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan confirmed here Tuesday,
dismissing rumors that incumbent WTO chief will continue his
office for another three years after his current three-year term
ends then.
</P>
<P>
Surin was quoted by Thai News Agency as saying that a
resolution of the WTO's General Assembly last year clearly
indicated that Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi would replace Mike Moore from New Zealand as
the world trade body's director-general in September 2002.
</P>
<P>
Surin dismissed as groundless recent rumors that Moore would
continue his office for another three years.
</P>
<P>
Prudent checks on legal principles have already been made that
the world trade watchdog can be led by two directors who shares a
six-year term, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The final decision of the General Assembly of the WTO on the
issue in July 1999 must be irrevocable and be strictly followed so
that the world trade body's creditability and prestige would
always be maintained, Surin pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
