<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Tuesday, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said on
Monday that increased direct investment could help cushion the
impact of rising fuel prices on the economy, according to a
government report.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the report as saying that the Finance Ministry
's economic forecasts, which are currently under revision due to
pressure from higher oil prices, should take into account other
non-oil price factors, especially investments.
</P>
<P>
Citing Board of Investment (BOI) figures, he noted that during
the first half of the year, projects seeking BOI promotional
privileges were up over 100 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He also said that apart from a pick-up at the BOI, new
investments were coming at a time when a number of local
industries, including plastic, pulp and battery business, have not
reached full production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The increasing investments will further boost Thai export,
which is regarded as the main engine of Thailand's economic
recovery, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Annual inflation rate in India fell by 0.65
percent to 5.75 percent for the week ended on August 5, mainly on
account of a drastic 1.1 percent decline in the prices of primary
articles, official statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
The rate of inflation, based on wholesale price index, fell to
5.75 percent (provisional) from 6.40 percent a week earlier,
according to a weekly report issued on Sunday by the Reserve Bank
of India, central bank of the country.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline in the reference week was mainly due to a 7
percent fall in prices of fruits and vegetables, the report said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- The Vietnam-Laos Intergovernmental Committee held its
mid-term meeting here Monday to discuss measures of promoting
cooperation between the two countries, according to Vietnam News
Agency (VNA).
</P>
<P>
The two sides assessed the implementation of this year's
cooperation agreement and sought ways to promote ties,
particularly through the writing of a draft cooperation agreement
between the two countries for the 2001-2005 period.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Denmark will grant non-refundable aid of 62 million U.
S. dollars and expert help for 36 months to a project to support
Vietnam's agriculture sector in the 2000-2005 period, Vietnam News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
With this project, Denmark becomes Vietnam's largest foreign
non-refundable donor, with most of the funds going to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, Danish experts will transfer to farmers
technology for post-harvest preservation, seedling treatment,
integrated pest management, and livestock breeding development.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar produces 200,000 tons of edible oil annually
while importing 100,000 tons of such oil to help fulfill its
domestic demand, says the Myanmar Facts and Figures booklet
currently published by the country's Ministry of Information.
</P>
<P>
In addition to cultivation of major oil crops such as groundnut,
sesame sunflower and mustard, cultivation of soy bean and oil palm
is also being extended for extracting edible oil.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar annually cultivates over 650,000 hectares of oil crops,
of which over 450,000 hectares are covered by groundnut, while
over 200,000 hectares by sunflower.
</P>
<P>
According to official disclosure, annual import of edible oil
is valued at 72.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam's gross domestic product GDP) growth is
estimated to reach 6.5-7 percent in 2000, Vietnam's official news
agency VNA reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The growth will be one percent higher than the target set by
Vietnam's National Assembly, according to the Ministry of Planning
and Investment (MPI).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam registered a year-on-year increase of 6.2 percent in
GDP in the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The MPI also forecast that Vietnam may be possible this year to
obtain increases of 5 percent in agriculture, forestry and
fisheries, 15 percent in industrial production, and 6 percent in
services, in comparison to the set targets of 3.3-4.0 percent, 10.
5-11.0 percent and 5.0-5.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China's information technology industry is to retain
an annual growth rate of above 20 percent in the next five years,
according Vice Minister of Information Industry Lu Xinkui.
</P>
<P>
Lu told the 16th World Computer Congress opened here Monday
that the output of the IT industry will double in the next five
years to account for 5 percent of the nation's GDP.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government places great importance on the
development of the IT industry as a pillar industry of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Lu noted that in the next five years, China will focus on
building infrastructures of a national information network,
accelerating the development of information technology and IT
industry and pushing forward the application of information
technology in all sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
CHONGQING -- The central government of China is to appropriate
9 billion yuan (about 1 billion U.S. dollars) to improve the
country's environment this year.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest sum of government money for environment
protection since the founding of the People's Republic in 1949,
said Hu Hengyang, deputy head of the Agricultural and Economic
Department under the State Development Planning Commission, at a
national conference that opened Monday in Chongqing, the largest
metropolis in western China.
</P>
<P>
China is working on nine environmental protection projects. The
project to regenerate the country's natural forest belts has cost
6.4 billion yuan. The state will provide an additional of 1.3
billion yuan for the project in the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The country will invest 1 billion yuan to plant trees and grass
on barren hills, 400 million yuan to expand windbreak belts and 1.
6 billion yuan to improve the environment in 370 counties.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, China has spent 27 billion
yuan on improving the environment since 1998.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China's top legislature, the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress (NPC), will amend the tax
administration law to ensure the state's revenues, safeguard the
legitimate rights of tax-payers and penalize illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
Jin Renqing, director of the State Administration of Taxation,
presented amendment explanations to the 17th session of the NPC
Standing Committee, which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In amending the tax law, more emphasis will be put on the tax
collection, which will ensure the timely and adequate collection
of taxes.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The State Council Monday set up 15 supervisory
boards in 16 major state-owned banking institutions.
</P>
<P>
Yan Haiwang, deputy secretary of the Financial Work Committee
of the Communist Party of China Central Committee, told the
supervisors that the establishment of the supervisory boards in
major banking institutions is aimed to improve the banking sector'
s supervision and quality of its state-owned assets.
</P>
<P>
The 16 banking institutions include eight banks, four assets
management corporations, three insurance companies and one
securities company.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China's lawmakers Monday began to examine a draft
proposal submitted by the State Council for the issuance of
another 50 billion yuan (about 6.07 billion U.S. dollars) of long-
term treasure bonds during the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng elaborated on the draft
proposal to the on-going 17th meeting of the Standing Committee of
the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that the pro-active financial policy, adopted in 1998,
should be continued to inject investment into infrastructure in a
bid to push domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The additional issuance of T-bond will be mainly used to
support the development in China's central and western areas, the
minister said.
</P>
