<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Emerald Trade Costs Zambia $300 Million last Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unscrupulous dealers have been blamed for the unsavory trade,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The paper's investigations revealed that in the previous year,
Kagem Minerals has allegedly been undermined by the unscrupulous
dealers and has failed to perform as one of the world's leading
emeralds producers.
</P>
<P>
The failure by the Copperbelt Province-based gemstone mining
firm to perform well on the global market has been attributed to
methods used by some dealers in auctioning the precious stones on
the local market before they are off loaded on the world markets
at very high prices.
</P>
<P>
According to Kagem insiders and gemstones auctioneers' sources
in Lusaka, the named dealers have been stage-managing auctions at
which a curtail of business persons linked to a named company
offer very low prices for the stones.
</P>
<P>
What has been happening is that the same dealers organize
people they know to attend the auctions at which the emeralds are
sold. At such auctions, the bidders are strictly told to
undervalue the stones and offer very low prices, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Such illegal business practices have resulted in the country
receiving very little or no income at all from the sales of the
stones on the world market. They are illegally reaping from Zambia,
" the source said.
</P>
<P>
Another Lusaka mining source stated: " on the global market,
Colombia which has by far very inferior stones compared to those
of Zambia, managed to reap more than three billion U.S. dollars
but the records we have is that Zambia only managed a meager 300,
000 dollars, yet we're regarded as the world's biggest producer of
high quality emeralds."
</P>
<P>
A mining sector stakeholder, Ben Mulenga, has since written to
the Zambian government, various political parties and relevant
government ministries to protest against the illegal practices.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Mulenga said that the practice by dealers to
involve individuals and firms they can dictate terms to, is
detrimental to the development of the gemstone and mining sector
of the country.
</P>
<P>
He called for quick government intervention in the business,
adding that the state's intervention will normalize operations and
the running of the mining firm.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Ministry of Finance and Economic Development officials
revealed that the government is already reviewing recommendations
from the Zambia Privatization Agency on how best operations can be
normalized at Kagem Minerals which was privatized in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
