<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Declares Wednesday Mourning Day for Kursk Crew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
on Tuesday declared Wednesday a day of mourning for the crew of
the sunken nuclear submarine Kursk.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian nuclear submarine Kursk sank in the Barents Sea on
August 12, 2000, its crew perished. Expressing my grief for the
perished and condolences to their families and relatives, I
announce August 23, 2000 a day of mourning in the Russian
Federation," Putin said in a decree released by the Kremlin press
service.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Russian flag will be flown at half-mast
throughout the country. Cultural institutions, television and
radio broadcasting companies will be ordered to cancel their
entertainment events and shows in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government, along with government agencies across
the country, will take necessary measures to help the families of
the dead, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, the Itar-Tass news agency quoted the Northern
Fleet headquarters as saying that to care for the numerous
sorrowful relatives of the dead crewmen will be the main task at
this moment for the Command of the Russian Navy and local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Many of the relatives are suffering from shock and need urgent
medical aid. However, they insist on a request that the command
bring them to the tragedy scene in the Barents Sea to mourn their
beloved ones.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters said that if weather permits, the relatives
might be brought to the scene on board the hospital ship Svir.
</P>
<P>
Monday, the Russian government decided to grant the family of
each dead crewman 1.5 million rubles (about 54,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Russian Northern Fleet commander, Admiral Vyacheslav Popov,
on Tuesday praised the Kursk crew for honestly serving their
homeland to the last minute and carrying out their duty to the end.
</P>
<P>
Tass Tuesday cited experts as saying that the crew behaved
heroically by shutting down the sub's two nuclear reactors in the
last minutes of their lives.
</P>
<P>
The sailors would have had a chance to stay alive if the
reactors had not been shut down, specialists believe. However, the
crewmen who survived the terrible explosions on the sub's board
took a difficult decision to shut down the reactors in order to
avoid radioactive contamination, instead of timely escape and
leaving the nuke engines in work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Navy Denies Report on More Kursk Crew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russian navy Tuesday denied
media reports that there were 130 crewmen instead of 118 aboard
the sunken nuclear submarine Kursk, the Interfax news agency
quoted the navy as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The real exact number has been announced, and it is now and
will remain 118 people. It is an official roster of the personnel
on the submarine," Igor Dygalo, aide to the commander-in-chief of
the Russian navy, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with all requirements that have to be met, when
organizing military training, and especially the military training
of submarine forces, the presence of additional people, so-called
passengers, at sea is prohibited," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"We said right away that besides the crew the submarine was
also carrying representatives of the headquarters of the unit, to
which this submarine belonged, and one civil specialist. This is
all normal practice. Ships often go to military training with
representatives of the headquarters of their unit and industry
representatives on board," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The Komsomolskaya Pravda daily on Tuesday quoted sources as
saying that there may have been civilians among the 12 persons
that were not regular crew members of Kursk.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear submarine went down to sea when it was attending a
military exercise in the Barents Sea on August 12. Rescue efforts
were declared futile and all the 118 sailors on board declared
dead on Monday. The cause of the tragedy remains hazy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
