<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli and Palestinian security agents have uncovered an
Islamic terror network and arrested 23 people, some of whom are
linked with Osama bin Laden, America's most wanted terrorist.
</P>
<P>
The arrests have taken place over the past few months and
include three Israeli Arabs who were linked with the Islamic
movement.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior security source, the terrorists planned to
carry out a number of attacks aimed at causing mass casualties. The
aim was to disrupt the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli police detectives Monday located the missing American
intelligence officer, Jeremiah Mathis, in a youth hostel in the
southern desert town of Mitzpeh Ramon.
</P>
<P>
Since finding him, detectives have been trying to convince
Mathis that he needs to return to the United States. The police
have no legal authority to arrest him or extradite him to the U.S.,
so if they fail to convince him to return, they will have to
release him.
</P>
<P>
Mathis filed an application for new immigration status with the
Israeli Interior Ministry ten days ago. The request file has been
transferred to the police.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's water crisis necessitates the immediate import of
water from Turkey and the establishment of two desalination plants,
not just the one plant approved by the ministerial economics
committee, Water Commissioner Shimon Tal said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations with Ankara on the import of 45 million cubic
meters of water in a year in old oil tankers have stalled over the
question of price.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The chief of staff in Israeli Prime Minister's office Haim
Mandel-Shaked Monday stepped down from his position following harsh
criticisms of Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Shaked, considered one of Barak's closest aides, had originally
been due to leave his post in October, after the Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
Barak told his Labor Party upper echelon on Monday that the
aftershocks caused by resignations in his office will pass quickly.
The prime minister said he will not immediately replace Shaked, and
that his duties will be split between National Security Adviser
Danny Yatom and Director-General Yossi Kucik. 
</P>
</TEXT>
