<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
tap foreign aid in developing medical facilities to meet the
health needs of the people, particularly those in Mindanao, given
its limited budget next year, a senior official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez said in a radio speech that
while the department's budget for 2001 is less than that of last
year, foreign aid packages are on the pipeline to augment funds
for medical services.
</P>
<P>
"The Health Department has on the pipeline approved hospital
improvement projects intended to make for the reduction,"
Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
He said the department is now negotiating for contracts to
improve the Zamboanga Medical Center through a Spanish loan, and
has a 15-million-dollar Japanese grant to upgrade the Davao
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
The operation of these medical facilities, he said, is in line
with the directive of President Joseph Estrada to make quality
medical services accessible to Mindanao's poor residents. 
