<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Train Tragedy Death Toll Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in Sunday's train
explosion disaster at the Athi River railway station, some 30
kilometers southeast of Kenya's capital Nairobi, rose to 25 as
seven victims died at hospitals Monday, media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy occurred at 00:10 a.m. as nine wagons carrying
liquefied gas and crude oil detached with the train and rolled
back downhill and exploded on impact after derailing. Sixteen
people died on the spot and two died on their way to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Another 27 victims are still fighting for their survival in
intensive care at the Kenyatta National Hospital and the Nairobi
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that two people suffered serious burns on Sunday
night following a second round of explosions at the accident site.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry team into the disaster still had not been appointed
Monday night, waiting for consultations before the Minister of
Information, Transport and Communications can appoint the team.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that when finally commissioned, the team will
study the possibilities of both sabotage and negligence as being
causes of the crash.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, a commuter train in western Kenya derailed,
killing 13 passengers and injuring more than 30 others. In March
last year, a passenger train jumped the rail at Tsavo,
southeastern Kenya, killing 32 people including several foreigners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
