<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Homes for Three Gorges Dam Immigrants (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- In three years, Fengjie, a
county in southwest China's Chongqing municipality, will sink to
the bottom of a huge reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Over a million people who live in Fengjie and 12 nearby
counties in the Three Gorges Dam area will have to leave when a
great reservoir, part of the world's largest hydraulic project,
will form in 2003 and devour everything in the basin.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the local government is racing against time to put
up new towns in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of others still have to travel long
distances, some as far to Shanghai in east China, to live, though
now the capacity of the new settlement is limited.
</P>
<P>
Not far from the old one, a new town of Fengjie has almost
taken shape. Despite the fact that Fengjie has yet to unveil its
face, people can tell from its primary design that like the other
12 towns, it has been carefully planned.
</P>
<P>
The residential districts are multi-functional like modern
cities, the buildings are in various styles, trees and flowers dot
the green belt that take up 60 percent of the total area of town.
</P>
<P>
For the moment, Fengjie is like a huge construction site. Major
buildings like shopping centers, banks and insurance company
offices have been completed, while hundreds of other offices and
residential buildings are under construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
