<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to Repair Ancient City Ruins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TURPAN (XINJIANG), August 22 (Xinhua) -- China plans to invest
a huge sum of money into the preservation project for an ancient
city in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17.5 million yuan (about 2.1 million U.S. dollars)
will be poured into repairs of the Jiaohe Ruins, the world's
biggest and best-protected relics of clay-built city.
</P>
<P>
Located some 20 km. east of Turpan, the ruins of Jiaohe,
meaning "old city between two rivers", is an ancient frontier army
citadel of the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
As the capital of Turpan's earliest residents of the Cheshi
State, the 220,000-square-meter city is also the most intact
capital relics of the country.
</P>
<P>
Yue Feng, president of the Cultural Heritage Administration of
Xinjiang, said that repair work will be done to the temples,
eastern city gate, ancient houses, pagodas and the thousand
Buddhas cave.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the administration has spent some 3.3
million yuan on the protection of the city, a religious and
cultural center of the region.
</P>
<P>
As a key link of the ancient Silk Road, the Jiaohe City had
both geographical and strategically significance. It was totally
destroyed in wars and has remained an eerie but beautiful sight in
the desert.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Su Gong Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TURPAN (XINJIANG), August 22 (Xinhua) -- Su Gong Tower, the
largest ancient tower in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, stands to the east of Turpan City, along with a
mosque which could accommodate 1,000 prayers.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1777, during the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), the tower
is 37 m. tall and 10 m. in diameter at the bottom. A 77-step
spiral stair leads up to the top. Its body is made of bricks in a
dozen pattern with a strong Islamic style.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the tower was made a State-level key protective unit.
</P>
<P>
The tower was built by the then Turpan king and his son, who
were leading a group of Uygur people, to show their loyalty to the
Qing government and Allah. Some local historians believe the
building was set up in memory of an anti-separatist war jointly
fought by people from Uygur, Han, Manchu and Hui groups.
</P>
<P>
In 1731, the Turpan Uygur group was relocated to Dunhuang by
the Qing government so as to avoid invasion rebels and 30 years
later, they were moved back to Turpan after the rebellion was
quelled by the Qing army.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Astana Ancient Tombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TURPAN (XINJIANG), August 22 (Xinhua) -- Astana Ancient Tombs,
in Turpan, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is called by some
archeologists as an underground historic museum.
</P>
<P>
The ancient bombs, two km. north of the ancient Gaochang, used
to be a public burial place for officials and ordinary people of
different ethnic groups in the ancient city of Gaochang.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, the ancient tombs have been excavated by
archeologists for 14 times and so far, 456 tombs have been
discovered with over 10,000 valuable relics unearthed. In 1985,
the tombs was made a State-level key protective unit.
</P>
<P>
Most of the relics found are scripts, murals, silk paintings
and earthen figurines, which reflect all aspects of the life at
the time. These relics are very useful for studying the history of
West China, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The Study on Turpan, or Turpanology, is as much known as the
Study on Dunhuang Grottoes. Scripts are the main part of the
research on Turpan.
</P>
<P>
Some of the silk paintings are the oldest of their kind to
depict the life of ancient women.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Bozklik Thousand-Buddha Grottoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TURPAN (XINJIANG), August 22 (Xinhua) -- Gaochang Grottoes, one
of the four largest grottoes in the world, are comprised of a
dozen grottoes groups in Turpan, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Among Gaochang Grottoes groups, Bozklik Thousand-Buddha
Grottoes group has the biggest number of grottoes and is the
richest in murals. It used to be a royal temple for the Gaochang
Uygur Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the Bozklik Grottoes were made a State-level key
protective unit.
</P>
<P>
Bozklik means decorative paintings in Turkish language.
</P>
<P>
Findings by archeologists show that the grottoes used to be
accompanied by big halls and corridors.
</P>
<P>
Bozklik now has 83 caves with a total of 1,200 sq.m. of murals
depicting religious life of Uygur before they converted to
Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
Bozklik Grottoes were abandoned in the fifteenth century when
Islam entered the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
