<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sets Up Tea Wholesale Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China's first wholesale tea market
was recently set up in Eqiao Town, Fanchang county of east China's
Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The market, including a bargaining building, 2,800 stalls in
more than 400 shops and other trade facilities, will become a
comprehensive place to conduct tea trade, storage, information
exchange and research according to the investor.
</P>
<P>
Eqiao Town, which has a hundreds of years of history in tea
trading, is known as the "No.1 tea market" in south China.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, about 15 million kilograms of
tea is traded there every year, and the tea goes to 27 provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions and to many foreign
countries such as Russia, Japan and some East Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
