<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese cities, namely
Beijing and Taiyuan, reported slight air pollution today, with the
highest pollution reading at 147 in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two or fairly good air
quality was recorded in 30 cities.
</P>
<P>
These cities are Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Hohhot, Shenyang,
Dalian, Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong,
Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Nanning, Chongqing,
Guiyang, Xi'an, Lanzhou, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of the cities, except Chongqing and Guiyang
where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Ten cities -- Fuzhou, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai,
Haikou, Chengdu, Kunming, Lhasa and Yinchuan -- reported excellent
air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution reading: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution reading: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
