<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia, Slovenia Discuss Integration with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Slovak Foreign Minister Eduard
Kukan and his visiting Slovenian counterpart Alojz Peterle agreed
on Monday that when the European Union will admit new members and
which country will join it first will depend on political factors
rather than economic ones.
</P>
<P>
Peterle told a press conference after talks with Kukan that the
EU should not drag its feet on its eastward expansion, on which
the final decision will be "stamped with the brand of politics."
</P>
<P>
Peterle expressed the hope that Slovenia and Solvakia would
strengthen cooperation in making preparations and becoming the
first countries to join the EU together with Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Kukan said that while Slovakia is accelerating negotiations
with the EU in all fields, when it will join the EU should depend
on political factors.
</P>
<P>
The EU, and Central and East European countries have been at
odds over the timing of the eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Central and East European countries have asked the EU to
honor its promise to admit new members at the beginning of 2003,
while the EU insists that the expansion should be postponed
because the applicant countries failed to meet the requirements
set by it.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission said recently that the EU will accept new
members in 2005 at the earliest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
