<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set up National Technical University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will soon set up a
National Technical University for the benefit of the large number
of youth engaged in the fields of vocational and technical
education, the official Daily News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Vocational Training and Rural Industries Amarasiri
Dodangoda was quoted as saying that the existing university system
had not introduced any degree course for technical and vocational
education although at present there were 13 universities in the
country that offered eight types of degrees to youth.
</P>
<P>
He said the lack of technical education was one of the major
constraints for training human resources in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the new university would change the education
system of the country and re-orient technical and vocational
education to suit the present day needs.
</P>
<P>
He added that the education provided to the students at the new
university should help uplift the development process in the
country. In this context immediate steps had to be taken to
develop the country's technical and vocational education which
provided the highest contribution to develop human resources.
</P>
<P>
The proposed university would be a unique opportunity for
students and professional engaged in technical and vocational
fields to upgrade their skills. 
</P>
