<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workplace Accidents in Vietnam Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to official statistics, at least one person has died
in a workplace accident in the country for each day of the last
three-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 2000, there were 23 percent more
workplace accidents (totaling of 1,418 cases) than in the same
period last year. These produced 1,479 victims, 17 percent more
than in the first half of 1999. Of which, 174 were killed and 443
people seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of the fatalities in the first half of the
year is slightly down on 1999's comparative period.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's main heavy industry hubs - Ho Chi Minh City, Hai
Phong, Quang Ninh, and Thai Nguyen - have the worst figures on
workplace injuries and fatalities.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 2000, more than 10 billion
Vietnamese dong (VND) (714,286 U.S. dollars) was spent on labor
accident compensation compared with 13.216 billion VND (944,000 U.
S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
A number of experts here said that the real figures could be 10
times higher than those declared above.
</P>
<P>
According to the recent statistics of the Ministry of Labor,
War Invalids and Social Affairs, accidents caused by workers
violating regulations on technological safety accounted for 51.1
percent of the total labor accident cases, while 10.2 percent were
caused by poor working conditions with unsafe equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
