<HEADLINE> L. American Coffee Producers To Discuss Price Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from nine Latin
American coffee producing countries will meet Wednesday in Costa
Rica to discuss the fall in coffee bean price at the international
market.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss the measures needed to arrest the
fall, including cutting production, Secretary General of the
Coffee Producing Countries Association (CPCA), Roveiro Silva, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The price fell to 78.4 dollars per sack last Friday, one of the
lowest in the last decades.
</P>
<P>
CPCA groups Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador, Nicaragua,
Costa Rica, Colombia, Peru and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
These countries would refrain from exporting 10 million 46-
kilogram sacks of the 2000-2001 harvest.
</P>
<P>
CPCA seeks to raise the price to 125 dollars per sack in the
next two harvests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
