Athletics Association (AAAA) President Muhammad Bob Hasan of
Indonesia at a congress to elect a new president is in doubt due
to his detention in an Attorney General's Office cell here.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Amateur Athletics Association (PASI) Secretary-
General Tigor Tanjung said that Hasan's lawyer Hotma Sitompul had
requested the Attorney General's Office allow Hasan to be present
at the congress next month.
</P>
<P>
"We still haven't received any answer from the Attorney General
's Office. It will be really difficult if the AAAA president is
absent from the congress because he must give an accountability
report," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General's Office spokesman Yushar Yahya said that the
possibility of Hasan attending the congress was very slim.
</P>
<P>
"Probably he won't be able to attend the congress," Yahya said.
</P>
<P>
The AAAA statutes say that should the president be absent,
senior vice president Khalid bin Thani Al-Thani can replace him.
</P>
<P>
Hasan and four other candidates -- Al-Thani of Qatar, Eisa Al-
Dashti of Kuwait, Suresh Kalmadi of India and Muhammad Imtiaz Ali
of Pakistan -- are candidates for the next president for the 2000
to 2004 tenure. 
