<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Former Armed Forces
Commander Gen. Wiranto has been suspected to be involved in the
violation of human rights which took place in the former
Indonesian province of East Timor, the Indonesian Observer daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Luhut Pangaribuan, a member of the expert team
from the probe into human rights violations in East Timor, the
findings announced by the Commission of Inquiry into Human Rights
Abuse in East Timor and the probe conducted by an expert team did
not differ in substance and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, a close aide of former president Soeharto, quitted as
Coordinating Minister for Political and Security Affairs in March
this year to facilitate the probe into the alleged human rights
violations in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian military was accused of killing thousands of
people in East Timor before or after a direct ballot which led to
the breakaway of East Timor from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Pangaribuan also said that an international tribunal was an
alternative when it came to bring the alleged human rights
violators to justice.
</P>
<P>
The expert team of the Commission of Inquiry into Human Rights
Abuse in East Timor Monday held a meeting at the Attorney General
Office to discuss the legal basis to be applied to try the case,
he added. 
