<HEADLINE> Venezuela Denies Accords with Colombian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan government denied
on Monday to have any sort of agreement with Colombian rebel
groups, saying that it is only in its interest to collaborate in
Colombia's peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say in a clear and definite fashion, that there is
no agreement neither with ELN, nor with FARC," said Venezuela's
Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel in response to a statement by
the National Liberation Army (ELN), the second largest guerrilla
group in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
"There is no document, nor talks that could be considered as a
formal agreement between the Venezuelan government and these
guerrilla groups" from Colombia, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Commander Pablo", ELN head in the regions of Arauca, Boyaco
and Casanare, said in an interview released on Monday by the
Caracas newspaper "El Nacional" that the guerrilla group respects
the conditions of the non-aggression pact which holds with the
Venezuelan government.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said the ELN is not involved in any kind of
criminal activity within Venezuelan territory, denying the rumors
that the guerrilla group is responsible for the kidnapping of the
Venezuelan entrepreneur Richard Boulton one month ago, whose
whereabouts are unknown.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela and Colombia share an extensive 2,219-kilometer
border, commonly known for kidnappings, blackmail, robbery and
drugs trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
