<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North-South Divide in Britain Predicted to Get Bigger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) - A group of British leading
economists have predicted that England's north-south divide is set
to grow bigger this year.
</P>
<P>
The Oxford Economic Forecasting estimated that the southeastern
region of England outside London will see an economic growth of 3.
7 percent, and eastern England and greater London will have a
growth of 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the west Midlands economy is expected to grow by 2.8
percent and north-east England by 2.7 percent, the consultant
company added.
</P>
<P>
Trade Minister Richard Caborn said that the government admitted
there are regional differences but the gap is narrowing.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Prime Minister Tony Blair attempted to dispel
the image of a north-south divide when he conducted a two-day tour
of north-west England.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a visit to Manchester, Blair said the north-
south split is "an over-simplistic explanation of the problems
that regional economies face."
</P>
<P>
He said: "The real divide is between the haves and have-nots,
whatever part of the country you are in."
</P>
<P>
But, in April this year, his views were rebuffed by an all-
party select committee on education and employment, which said
there was still a distinctive north-south pattern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
