<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian President Checks Security Plan for Clinton Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres
Pastrana met Monday with the directors of the Police Department
and the Administrative Department of Security (ADS) to examine the
security arrangements for U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to
the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place in the Navy's Atlantic Ocean Base at
Cartagena, one of the country's coastal cities, where Pastrana and
Clinton will hold a meeting on August 30.
</P>
<P>
ADS director in the state of Bolivar, Jorge Alberto Lagos, said
the security requirements raised by U.S. officials are intended to
avoid terrorist actions and to guarantee Clinton's safety.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Humberto de la Calle said the state security
agencies will be accountable for Clinton's safety during his stay
at Cartagena, although he explained there will be U.S. officials
present to protect the president.
</P>
<P>
"Security is a Colombian matter, but the U.S. will participate
with a number of officials in charge of the protection of
President Clinton," said De la Calle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
