<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Heritage Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China's historic and cultural
relics will be better protected and properly utilized during the
development of the country's western regions, government officials
have vowed.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Xinmiao, deputy head of the State Bureau of Cultural
Relics, said that his bureau would increase investment in cultural
relics protection in the west of the country.
</P>
<P>
The bureau is now studying the situation to determine how much
cash will be needed, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Having a population of about 370 million, Western China covers
the provinces of Shaanxi, Yunnan, Guizhou, Gansu, Sichuan and
Qinghai, the autonomous regions of Tibet, Ningxia, Xinjiang,
Guangxi and Inner Mongolia, and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Many parts of the region have a great number of historical
sites, including the ancient capital of Xi'an, Gansu's Dunhuang
and Chongqing's Dazu, both famous for their Buddhist relics.
</P>
<P>
However, current protection measures in the west are not
sufficient to manage the vast number of sites and relics in the
area, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, a six-story stupa was stolen in Gansu
Province, and Dunhuang's Buddhist frescoes have been seriously
damaged over the years due to the number of visitors.
</P>
<P>
Zheng stressed that historical sites and relics in the west
must be used according to their specific nature. And he
recommended to limit the number of visitors to some sites.
</P>
<P>
Wang Honghua, director of Chongqing Cultural Bureau echoed the
Zheng's view to acknowledge that the need to protect the area's
historical sites is urgent.
</P>
<P>
The municipality has rescued more than 12,000 cultural relics
since the Three Gorges Project began, Wang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Killed in Helicopter Crash in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A helicopter owned by the
Indonesian Navy crashed Monday afternoon in a rice field in
bojonegore regency,East Jakarta, killing all five of its crew,
Antara news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The crash took place at 3:00 p.m. near Deru village in
Sumberejo sub-district, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Surabaya based Eastern Fleet Command, Lt. Col.
Ditya Soedarsono said the BO-type chopper was on its way to
Surabaya, capital of East Java province, from Jakarta when it
experienced engine trouble while refueling at a military base in
Semarang, the capital of Central Java province.
</P>
<P>
Ditya said he was researching the cause of the crash and the
chronology of the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
