<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia on Monday voiced regret at Israel's
attempts to "hinder the Middle East peace process," especially the
attempt to annex Jerusalem and giving some Palestinians Israeli
nationality.
</P>
<P>
This position was expressed at a weekly session of the Saudi
cabinet held in the western Saudi city of Jeddah chaired by King
Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, according to reports reaching here. (Saudi
Arabia-Israel-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan will continue to promote the Middle East peace
process but firmly rejects Israeli sovereignty over the holy city
of Jerusalem, Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Khatib said
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Answering an inquiry from members of the Palestinian Affairs
Committee of the House of Representatives (lower house), Khatib
stressed that Jerusalem is part of the Arab lands captured by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, and its future should be
decided in accordance with resolutions of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan will not compromise on its position that
Jerusalem belongs to the Arab and Muslim world and the holy city
should be handed over to the Palestinian National Authority, the
governing body of the Palestinians. (Jordan-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak warned Shas and
United Torah Judaism (UTJ) on Monday that if they join the efforts
to topple the government during the summer recess of the Knesset (
parliament), their interests would be greatly harmed.
</P>
<P>
Barak did not reveal what measures he will take to punish those
two parties, but said he would find ways of "being less
considerate" to their interests, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Prime Minister's Office told the Radio that
measures Barak would take against the two parties include
providing less funds to the Shas educational system and
considering passing legislation on conscripting religious students
to the army. (Israel-Barak-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Northern Fleet commander Vyacheslav Popov
confirmed that all the crew of the sunken submarine Kursk are dead,
the Interfax news agency reported Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"After jointly examining the Russian nuclear submarine Kursk
that sank in the Barents Sea during a military exercise on August
12, Russian and foreign experts have made the final conclusion
that the entire submarine is flooded and all the 118 crew is dead,
" Interfax cited Popov, who was in charge of the rescue operation,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The commander said that the rescue effort began immediately
after the accident and lasted throughout the following days. (No
Sub-survivor-Confirmation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Spokesman for former South African President
Nelson Mandela officially announced here Monday that a long
awaited Burundi peace agreement will be signed by all 19 warring
parties next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Judge Mark Bomani told a news conference that Mandela,
facilitator to the Burundi peace talks, has concluded that the
Burundi Peace and Reconciliation Agreement will be signed to end
the seven-year bloody civil war in the tiny central African state.
(Tanzania-Burundi Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian security forces have
arrested 23 Arab terrorist suspects who were accused of planning
to carry out terrorist attacks aimed at sabotaging the Mideast
peace process, a senior Israeli security official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The suspects, including 20 Palestinians and three Israeli Arabs,
all belong to militant Islamic groups, with some having links with
Saudi Arabia-born militant Osama bin Laden, according to the
official. (Israel-Palestinian-Arrests)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A poll of likely voters released on Monday put
Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore ahead of his Republican
rival George W. Bush for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The poll jointly conducted by CNN, USA Today and Gallup had
Gore at 47 percent, Bush at 46 percent, Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan
at 2 percent. (US-Gore-Bush-Poll) 
</P>
</TEXT>
