<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Leader Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government
Monday said the main rebel movement in the country, the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF), now has a new leader to succeed
the detained Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcast Corporation (BBC) quoted a Sierra Leonean
governmental statement as saying that the new leader is Issa Sesay,
RUF's battlefield commander since his predecessor Sam Bockarie
went to Liberia last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Sierra Leonean government
obtained information from a source closing to Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo and the Mali President Alpha Konare, who are now
in Sierra Leone on a peace mission.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government also plans to release some 170
RUF fighters in what it called the interests of a sustainable
peace, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, founder of the RUF, launched the civil war in Sierra
Leone in 1991. After being captured in May, he is now being held
in government custody at an unknown location and will face trial
for human rights offenses.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council has recently approved the
establishment of a court to try war criminals in Sierra Leone.
</P>
</TEXT>
