<HEADLINE> Mandelson Meets Security Chiefs on Escalating Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Peter Mandelson met the security chiefs Tuesday to
discuss the escalating violence between the province's two main
pro-British Protestant paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson and his security chiefs made no comment after their
meeting. Although behind-the-scenes attempts were being made to
get the rival organizations to negotiate some sort of truce,
political representatives ruled out any early talks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after two men were shot dead Monday in an
escalation of a dispute between the pro-British Ulster Volunteer
Force (UVF) and the Ulster Defense Association (UDA).
</P>
<P>
Monday night was a mainly trouble-free, but there was a tense
atmosphere on the streets of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The two dead men, Jackie Coulter, a prominent member of the UDA,
and Robbie Mahood, were shot on the Crumlin Road in north Belfast
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, crowds attacked the Shankill Road offices of the
Progressive Unionist Party (PUP), which has links with the UVF,
and a taxi in separate incidents.
</P>
<P>
The police arrested a number of people and seized arms.
</P>
<P>
The shootings followed a weekend of tension between the rival
loyalist paramilitaries on the Shankill Road.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson said the latest outbreak of violence had "nothing to
do with politics" but was a result of "squalid murderous gang
warfare."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Mandelson decided to step up security by resuming
army patrols in some parts of Belfast and increasing the police
presence on the streets.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of feuding loyalist paramilitaries in Northern Ireland
were urged to agree to a mediation process in a bid to stop their
shooting war escalating into a full-scale bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
With dozens of police and troops on the streets of Belfast to
keep the rival UDA and UVF factions apart, politicians on all
sides, including Sinn Fein, called for an end to the violence.
</P>
<P>
Gary McMichael, leader of the Ulster Democratic Party, the UDA'
s political wing, said, "This infighting is tearing loyalism apart.
Those involved should take stock of the implications of continued
internecine violence and realize that they are on a road to
nowhere. "
</P>
<P>
Billy Hutchinson of the Progressive Unionist Party, the UVF's
political wing, said mediation talks would have to get under way
at some stage. "No matter how many people die, sooner or later
people will talk. We have to find a mediator who is respected on
both sides."
</P>
<P>
Mitchel McLaughlin, Sinn Fein's national chairman, said, "The
leaderships of these loyalist organizations must get their act
together. They must assert discipline within their groups and end
this shooting war." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
