<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S&AMP;P's Analysis: Asian Auto Industry in Recovery Mode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Asia will account for a
growing proportion of global auto industry demand and production
for the future, but the short-term picture remains less buoyant,
according to a report released Tuesday by Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
In the next decade, vehicle demand in Asia, excluding Japan, is
expected to increase at a compound average annual rate of 8.3
percent to reach 14.8 million units in 2010, the report said. By
2010, Asia, excluding Japan, will account for 20 percent of global
demand excluding Africa and the Middle East. Including Japan, the
region's share of global sales is expected to be 30 percent in
2010.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, demand still struggles from the blow
the region received with the economic crisis of the late 1990s.
Doubts are beginning to reappear about the sustainability of the
recovery.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, total vehicle demand in Asia had declined 18.3 percent
to 10.9 million units. The recovery in 1999 was impressive, with
total demand rising by 9.5 percent to 11.9 million units. While
Japan, the region's largest market, continued to stagnate in 1999,
South Korea registered big gains, with sales rising by 493,000
units and production by 888,000 units. Thailand, Malaysia, India
and China also held up well.
</P>
<P>
Total vehicle demand in Asia is expected to reach 12.7 million
units this year, up 7.2 percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Japan's role in Asia is reducing and
in 1999, non-Japanese vehicle demand exceeded Japanese demand. By
2005, sales in non-Japanese Asia are expected to be 9.9 million
units compared to Japanese demand of 6.9 million units. By 2010,
two-thirds of all vehicle sales in Asia will be outside of Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
