<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes Zimbabwe's Crackdown on Farm Squatters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government Wednesday applauded Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
for his crackdown on illegal land occupation.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet spokesman Joel Netshitenze told reporters in Pretoria
that "developments in the last 48 hours do demonstrate that they
were committed to what they had indicated to our delegation."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a promise made by Mugabe to South African
President Thabo Mbeki that war veterans would be removed from
white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki met with Mugabe in Harare on August 2, and Mugabe
announced after the meeting that his government would remove war
veterans from hundreds of white-owned farms and resettle them to
land acquired by the government within the coming four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Since February this year, about 1,600 white-owned farms have
been occupied by veterans who urged the government to speed up a
program to redistribute land from whites to landless black
peasants.
</P>
<P>
According to Netshitenze, Zimbabwean police began a crackdown
on squatters Monday and Tuesday as an "implementation of the
undertaking to the South African delegation of the eviction of
those who are occupying farms that have not been designated."
</P>
<P>
The police demolished shacks built by war veterans on land
south of Harare and parceled out to homeless urban dwellers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the South African cabinet has agreed that its ministers
will continue to meet with their Zimbabwean counterparts in a bid
to help its northern neighbor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
