<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Not to Repudiate Foreign Debt: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Minister of Foreign
Affairs Alhaji Sule Lamido has ruled out the repudiation of the
country's foreign debt, saying this would amount to a breach of
its international obligation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to media on Wednesday in the capital Abuja, Lamido
said as a "responsible member of the international community and
with the tremendous respect it enjoys within this community",
Nigeria could not afford to repudiate its foreign debt, which is
estimated at 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The present administration would continue to discuss with the
creditor countries about the virtue of debt forgiveness, despite
of the prevailing negative attitude among them, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We want them to understand that this is the only way to ensure
a secure, prosperous and contented Africa which would help promote
world peace and continue to provide a ready market for their
exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's democratically-elected government of President
Olusegun Obasanjo has been campaigning for debt forgiveness since
its inception last May, arguing that this would enable it to
deliver the dividends of democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
