<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Political Bureau to Be Appointed: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf)
Wednesday said the new political bureau will not be elected, but
be appointed by First Secretary and Party President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Administration Diydmus Mutasa told the Zimbabwe
News Agency that no amendments have been made to the party's
constitution to provide for the elections at the special congress
set for December this year.
</P>
<P>
The new political bureau was not appointed at the party's fifth
national congress last year as members failed to agree on whether
Mugabe should continue appointing the members instead of them
being elected.
</P>
<P>
This would be the first time a special congress is called to
announce the political bureau. In the past, Mugabe would announce
the new members before the close of the national congress.
</P>
<P>
"The constitution is not yet changed," Mutasa said. "Everything
will be done according to the constitution and President Mugabe
will appoint the political bureau members."
</P>
<P>
According to the Zimbabwe News Agency, some other issues like
the endorsement of constitutional changes to allow a one-third
quota system of allocating positions to women would be on the
agenda of the special congress.
</P>
<P>
There was speculation that the special congress might consider
the issue of choosing a successor to Mugabe who is widely believed
to be considering to resign before the 2002 presidential election.
</P>
