<HEADLINE> S. Africa Prohibits Police Moonlighting for Private Security Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- South African Cabinet
Wednesday approved a bill to regulate private security companies
and stop police from moonlighting for them.
</P>
<P>
It is vital that private security companies act in accordance
with the Constitution, South African Safety and Security Minister
Steve Tshwete told reporters after a cabinet meeting in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"They (the private security companies) have more men and women
under arms than we have in the police service," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tshwete pointed out that it is a bad practice for police to
earn extra money by doing night duty for private security
companies.
</P>
<P>
"It adds to the stress levels they are experiencing," he said.
"You find that police officers doing that kind of moonlighting get
involved in ugly incidents."
</P>
<P>
This is neither in the interest of the police nor that of the
private security industry, the minister emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft legislation, members of the South African
National Defense Force will also not be allowed to work as private
security officers.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be tabled during the upcoming South African
parliamentary session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
