<HEADLINE> WB Approves 60 Million U.S. Dollars Credit to Tanzanian Poor Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has
approved a 60 million U.S. dollars credit to help Tanzanian poor
communities improve and sustain socioeconomic services and
opportunities, according to a statement issued here on Wednesday
by the World Bank country office.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be administered by the Tanzania Social Action
Fund Project, which aims to reduce the devastating effects of
poverty by providing opportunities for communities to participate
in and take charge of key decision-making processes at the local
level, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the fund will finance and support small demand-based
community initiatives in the social sectors that improve the
access to and delivery of social and economic services such as
health centers, school buildings, shallow wells, crop storage
facilities and markets.
</P>
<P>
"The project activities are designed to improve basic services
and protect vulnerable groups through community development
initiatives, public works program and institutional development,"
the document said.
</P>
<P>
Specific attention will also be given to HIV/AIDS prevention
programs, it added.
</P>
<P>
The credit, which is given by the International Development
Association, the World Bank's lending arm for the poorest
countries, is on standard terms of 40 years maturity, including 10
years grace.
</P>
<P>
Recent poverty data from the World Bank indicate that about
half of all Tanzanians live in poor households where each person
earns less than one dollar a day. Poverty is particularly
widespread in the countryside as almost 61 percent of the rural
population is poor compared to 39 percent of the urban population.
</P>
</TEXT>
