<HEADLINE> S. Africa Outlaws Dye-Stained Bank Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Any one in possession of
dye-stained bank notes could be carrying worthless money for which
there will be no compensation, the Banking Council of South Africa
(BCSA) announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The council said in a statement that the Reserve Bank (central
bank) of South Africa has decided to declare any such notes non-
legal tender.
</P>
<P>
For security reasons, most banks use cash boxes with a dye
mechanism to stain bank notes which in the case of a robbery will
be triggered as stolen money.
</P>
<P>
According to BCSA spokeswoman Adri Grobler, all banks have
been notified that the Reserve Bank would with immediate effect no
longer accept dye-stained notes from the institutions.
</P>
<P>
"The public should take note of this, and should take care to
check that they are not being given dye-stained notes by any
person or business as they could be the proceeds of crime," she
said.
</P>
<P>
She said the dye, which is normally pink, orange, blue or red,
could either be over the entire surface, around the edges or on
any part of the note.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman disclosed that special arrangements have been
made for banks to recover from the Reserve Bank the value of notes
dye-stained, provided the notes have remained continuously under
their control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Exports up, Imports Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The value of Tanzania's
exports recorded a 2.3 percent increase to 42.4 million U.S.
dollars in June this year from 41.4 million dollars in May, the
Central Bank of Tanzania said in its latest monthly economic
review.
</P>
<P>
However, its imports witnessed a 25.5 percent decrease over the
same comparison.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the exports of non-traditional
commodities including minerals and manufactured goods increased
from 26.9 million dollars in May to 33.4 million dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
But, traditional exports declined from 14.5 million dollars to
8.9 million dollars, which is mainly due to the weak world market
prices combined with declining export volumes, the review says.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the review shows imports of different items
decreased by 25.5 percent in June to 108.5 million dollars from
145.7 million dollars recorded during the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Oil imports decreased by 54.2 percent to 8 million dollars in
June from 17.3 million dollars in May due to a significant
decrease in volume.
</P>
<P>
Imports of food and foodstuffs also declined because it is
currently in the harvesting season in most of the cereal producing
areas in the country, added the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
