<HEADLINE> Angola Sets up Inter-Ministerial Commission to Reduce Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has set up
an inter-ministerial commission specialized in combating dire
poverty in the war-torn southwestern African country, an official
document said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest edition of the government's gazette,
this inter-ministerial commission is currently responsible for
drawing up a provisional document on strategies to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
The gazette noted that this move followed a monitored accord
signed between the Angolan government and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) recently.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which is to be coordinated by the Angolan Vice
Minister for Planning Eduardo Severim de Morais, is in charge of
surveying a set of related studies on the issue and assessing all
existing strategies on reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
When needed, the poverty-eliminating commission will summon
representatives of some professional organizations, employers'
associations, churches and non-governmental organizations for a
participative discussion on the situation of the civil society.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Ministry for Planning announced in late July that
some 67 percent of the Angolan population are suffering from dire
poverty, with 11 percent of them in utterly destitute.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, among the 12.6 million Angolan people,
only 30 percent have access to health service, 46 percent can get
potable water and only 16 percent have basic sanitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
