<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe University Joins U.S. Network to Prevent AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The University of Zimbabwe has
been selected to be a unit of the network funded by the National
Institutes of Health of the United States which is doing research
on the prevention of HIV and other sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Together with the University of California, the University of
Zimbabwe will receive research funds totaling up to 6 million U.S.
dollars over the next five years, according to a report from the
Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
By virtue of being part of the network, Zimbabwe will have the
opportunity to develop intervention studies targeted against HIV
infection and be part of future multicentre endeavors to the
prevention of HIV infection, the report said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current research in Zimbabwe already funded by the network
on trial includes a study that examines the effect of a spermicide
in preventing women against contracting HIV and other sexually
transmitted diseases and the effect of nevirapine drug in
preventing perinatal transmission of HIV in breast-feeding babies.
</P>
<P>
Other 11 countries in Africa, Asia and South America also have
joined the U.S. network.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is among the countries in the world with the highest
AIDS cases, with about 2,000 people dying from AIDS related
diseases per week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
