<HEADLINE> HIV Infection Rate in Uganda Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The HIV infection rate in Uganda
has reduced to the current 9.5 percent from 30.5 percent in 1980s
and early 1990s, Acting Director of Uganda Population Secretariat
Charles Zirarema told Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The HIV infection rate also witnessed 0.5 percentage point down
from 10 percent in the previous year, said Zirarema.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this reduction to the good leadership in Uganda
which is the most important weapon in fighting AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"The leadership in this country has opened up doors for the
people to go out and talk about AIDS freely," said Zirarema
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS is not only a health issue but also an issue on the
Ugandan development agenda, he said, adding that this has also
contributed to the reduction of HIV infection rate.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is one of a few countries in Africa which have achieved
success in fighting against the killer disease. The success is
also attributed to the enhanced awareness of the ordinary people
in the east Africa country. 
</P>
