<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Against High Expectations Upon Clinton's Nigeria Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has advised
Nigerians against an "exaggerated expectation" on this week's
visit of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Susan Rice, the U.S. Assistant Secretary for African Affairs,
Tuesday told Nigerian press via internet link that the complete
debt cancellation is "difficult to achieve".
</P>
<P>
Describing Nigeria a country "too rich to be poor, and too poor
to be rich", she said in Washington via web that Nigeria is not
eligible for the Highly Indebted Poor Country Initiative".
</P>
<P>
Noting only less than four percent of Nigeria's debt is owed to
the U.S., she however pledged that the U.S. will help Nigeria to
reschedule its staggering 30 billion U.S. dollar debt to make it "
manageable" and "not overly extraordinary".
</P>
<P>
But she also stressed that any debt relief is possible only in
the context that the reduced debt becomes investment in the
welfare of average Nigerians and the reduction is carried out in a
credit worthy way.
</P>
<P>
She said the U.S. has already increased its aid to Nigeria from
7 million dollars in 1998 to about 109 million in 2000, making the
country "by far the largest development partner in Africa."
</P>
