<HEADLINE> Tea Demand Low at Kenya's Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Activity slowed at Kenya's tea
auction this week due to lower demand, undermining prices for most
grades except the top ones, the East African Standard newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Top grades gained up to 10 U.S. cents per kg but mediums and
other lower grades were quoted softer.
</P>
<P>
"There was less and selective demand," Africa Tea Brokers said
in their weekly report.
</P>
<P>
Traders reported reduced demand from British, Pakistani, Yemeni
and Afghan buyers.
</P>
<P>
"This was a down market. We hope the prices will improve next
week," one trader said, adding that some buyers were finding
Kenyan prices high compared with other markets.
</P>
<P>
Prices rose at last week's auction, lifted by the return of
Egyptian buyers after a trade dispute between Nairobi and Cairo
was resolved.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, one of three largest black tea producers in the world,
exported 241,700 tons of tea to more than 40 countries. 
