<HEADLINE> Starving Wild Animals Invade Farms in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Hungry wild animals escaping
drought and famine in the vast Aberdare and Mt. Kenya national
parks in central Kenya have invaded people's farms destroying
crops and killing farmers, the East African Standard newspapers
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The animals including elephants and buffaloes have caused
massive destruction of food crops in parts of Nyeri District in
Central Province as the country is experiencing a prolonged
drought.
</P>
<P>
At the weekend, a 60-year-old farmer was trampled to death by
elephants which raided his farm in Sagana Village at the edge of
Mt. Kenya forest.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a herd of buffaloes attacked and seriously injured
two young men whom they encountered in Naro Moru division. The two
were admitted at Provincial General Hospital at Nyeri town in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Senior Warden Ibrahinm Rubia of the Aberdare National Park said
upon receiving the report of the buffalo attack, he immediately
sent some wardens in search of the animals and killed one buffalo
after it turned very violent.
</P>
<P>
Rubia explained that the animals in the national parks were
escaping the ravaging drought and their search for food was
leading them to people's farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
