<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changes Introduced in Kenya's Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Major changes have been
introduced in Kenya's military, including pegging future
promotions to academic performance and allowing women soldiers to
marry, the Daily Nation newspapers reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Officers will be required to undergo university level education
to be considered for promotion under a new mandatory scheme which
took effect in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The changes were approved in May by the Defense Council, the
country's highest decision-making organ on military affairs other
than the presidency.
</P>
<P>
To get promotion, officers now must earn certificates, diplomas,
bachelors and masters degrees in courses on military science
currently offered only at Egerton University in Nakuru, a city in
central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
They will be implemented in phases for the next 11 years until
July 1, 2012, when no major will be promoted to lieutenant-colonel
without having earned a masters degree in military science.
</P>
<P>
Under the changes, women soldiers and officers are now free to
marry either civilians or soldiers, following the integration of
the former Women Service Corp into other formations of the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
The changes are to replace the earlier one where officers and
soldiers had to volunteer for practical examinations set by the
military or undergo specialized training abroad as one of the
considerations to promotion.
</P>
<P>
It is also to avoid the tribalism, nepotism and party
affiliation which are sometimes felt to have influenced promotions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
