<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Seeks More Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government should
increase the defense budget to improve the performance of the
Uganda People's Defense Forces, Army Chief of Logistics Fred
Bogere has said at the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a dilemma. The situation is quite alarming. Until
the Ministry of Finance approves our budget as we present it, our
performance will remain minimal," Bogere told the parliament
committee on defense and internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said they had budgeted for 400 billion Uganda shillings (
about 250 million U.S. dollars) but were asked by the Ministry of
Finance to scale it down to 191 billion shillings, according to a
Wednesday report of the New Vision newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Bogere said 59 percent of this would be spent on wages and the
remaining 41 percent on welfare and others.
</P>
<P>
Edith Mwanje, undersecretary in the Ministry of Finance, said
however that budgets in all sectors were cut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000822.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Mostly on Steady Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved higher
Tuesday after the Federal Reserve left interest rates unchanged as
most analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 59.34 at 11,139.15
points. The blue chip index gained 33.33 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 5.06 at 3,958.21 points and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 1.35 at 1,498.13.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve announced its decision to stay on hold
after a meeting on rates today but warned that it may need to
raise rates later if price pressures build.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts had expected the central bank to leave rates
alone because recent reports showed that the U.S. economy is
slowing and inflation remains tame. The Federal Reserve has raised
rates six times in the past 14 months in an effort to cool off the
economy enough to prevent inflation from rising.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve's next meeting is in early October.
Analysts believed that in a presidential election year, an autumn
rate hike right before voters go to the polls is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Most banking and retail stocks rose on the rate decision. Among
them were J.P. Morgan and the Gap.
</P>
<P>
In the tech sectors, most software and computer stocks gained
while shares of semiconductor and telecommunications fell after a
strong rally in the previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 0.46 at 671.62 and the American Stock
Exchange index was up 2.23 at 922.75. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 1.01 at 517.46.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,465 up, 1,341 down and 583
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 815.10 million shares from 726.38
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
